], [[1969 American Football League Championship Game|1969]]\n| no_sb_champs = 2\n| sb_champs = [[Super Bowl IV|1969]] ([[Super Bowl IV|IV]]), [[Super Bowl LIV|2019]] ([[Super Bowl LIV|LIV]])\n| conf_champs =\n* '''[[AFC Championship Game|AFC]]:''' [[2019 NFL season|2019]]\n| div_champs = \n* '''AFL Western''': 1962, 1966\n* '''AFC West''': 1971, 1993, 1995, 1997, 2003, 2010, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n| playoff_appearances = \n* '''AFL''': [[1962 American Football League season|1962]], [[1966 American Football League Championship Game|1966]], [[1968 American Football League season|1968]], [[1969 American Football League Championship Game|1969]]\n* '''NFL''': [[1971\u201372 NFL playoffs|1971]], [[1986\u201387 NFL playoffs|1986]], [[1990\u201391 NFL playoffs|1990]], [[1991\u201392 NFL playoffs|1991]], [[1992\u201393 NFL playoffs|1992]], [[1993\u201394 NFL playoffs|1993]], [[1994\u201395 NFL playoffs|1994]], [[1995\u201396 NFL playoffs|1995]], [[1997\u201398 NFL playoffs|1997]], [[2003\u201304 NFL playoffs|2003]], [[2006\u201307 NFL playoffs|2006]], [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs|2010]], [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs|2013]], [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs|2015]], [[2016\u201317 NFL playoffs|2016]], [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs|2017]], [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs|2018]], [[2019\u201320 NFL playoffs|2019]]\n| no_playoff_appearances = 22\n| stadium_years = \n* [[Cotton Bowl (stadium)|Cotton Bowl]] (1960\u20131962)\n* [[Municipal Stadium (Kansas City, Missouri)|Municipal Stadium]] (1963\u20131971)\n* [[Arrowhead Stadium]] (1972\u2013present)\n}}\n\nThe '''Kansas City Chiefs''' are a professional [[American football]] team based in [[Kansas City, Missouri]]. The Chiefs compete in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) as a member club of the league's [[American Football Conference]] (AFC) [[AFC West|West]] division. The team was founded in 1960 as the '''Dallas Texans''' by businessman [[Lamar Hunt]] and was a charter member of the [[American Football League]] (AFL). (It is not associated with the [[National Football League|NFL]] [[Dallas Texans (NFL)|Dallas Texans]].) In 1963, the team [[Relocation of professional sports teams|moved]] to Kansas City and assumed its current name.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chiefs History 1960-1969|url=https://www.chiefs.com/team/history/1960s|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC |website=Chiefs.com |accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref> The Chiefs joined the NFL as a result of the [[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merger]] in 1970. The team is valued at over $2 billion.<ref name=\"Forbes\"/> Hunt's son, [[Clark Hunt|Clark]], serves as chairman and CEO. While Hunt's ownership stakes passed collectively to his widow and children after his death in 2006, Clark is the operating head of the franchise; he represents the Chiefs at all league meetings and has ultimate authority on personnel changes.\n\nThe Chiefs have won three AFL championships, in 1962, 1966, and 1969.<ref name=\"PFHOF\"/> They became the second AFL team (after the [[New York Jets]]) to defeat an NFL team in an [[Super Bowl|AFL\u2013NFL World Championship Game]], when they defeated the [[Minnesota Vikings]] in [[Super Bowl IV]]. The team's victory on January 11, 1970, was the final such competition before the leagues' merger went into full effect. The Chiefs were also the second team, after the [[Green Bay Packers]], to appear in more than one Super Bowl (and the first AFL team to do so) and the first to appear in the championship game in two different decades. Despite post-season success early in the franchise's history, winning five of their first six postseason games, the team struggled to find success in the playoffs for many years, including losing 10 of 11 playoff games from 1993 to 2017, which included an 8-game losing streak. Since then, the Chiefs have won 4 of their last 5 playoff games, including [[Super Bowl LIV]] in 2020, which earned the franchise their first championship in 50 years.\n\n==Franchise history==\n{{Further|History of the Kansas City Chiefs}}\n\n===Formation===\nIn 1959, [[Lamar Hunt]] began discussions with other businessmen to establish a professional football league that would rival the [[National Football League]].<ref name=\"PFHOF\">{{cite web|title=Pro Football Hall of Fame: Kansas City Chiefs |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/teams/kansas-city-chiefs/team-history/|publisher=Pro Football Hall of Fame|accessdate=January 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126011856/http://www.profootballhof.com/teams/kansas-city-chiefs/team-history/|archivedate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"AFL Origins\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs History \u2013 AFL Origins |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/team/chiefs-history.html|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Chiefs.com|accessdate=December 31, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302041703/http://www.kcchiefs.com/team/chiefs-history.html|archivedate=March 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=NFL|title=That Time the Chiefs Battled the Cowboys for Dallas' Hearts {{!}} NFL Highlights |date=November 3, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=za0eZR4Qj38|accessdate=November 4, 2017}}</ref> Hunt's desire to secure a football team was heightened after watching the [[1958 NFL Championship Game]] between the [[New York Giants]] and [[Baltimore Colts]].<ref name=\"AFL Origins\"/><ref name=\"Althaus 35\">Althaus, p. 35</ref> After unsuccessful attempts to purchase and relocate the NFL's [[Chicago Cardinals (NFL, 1920\u201359)|Chicago Cardinals]] to his hometown of [[Dallas, Texas]],<ref name=\"PFHOF\"/><ref name=\"History 60s\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs History \u2013 1960s|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/60s/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC |website=Chiefs.com|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609053609/http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/60s/|archivedate=June 9, 2008}}</ref> Hunt went to the NFL and asked to create an expansion franchise in Dallas. The NFL turned him down, so Hunt then established the [[American Football League]] and started his own team, the Dallas Texans, to begin play in 1960. Hunt hired a little-known assistant coach from the [[Miami Hurricanes football|University of Miami football team]], [[Hank Stram]], to be the team's head coach<ref name=\"AFL Origins\"/> after the job offer was declined by [[Bud Wilkinson]] and [[Tom Landry]].<ref name=\"AFL Origins\"/>\n\nAfter Stram was hired, Don Klosterman was hired as head scout, credited by many for bringing a wealth of talent to the Texans after luring it away from the NFL, often hiding players and using creative means to land them.\n\n[[File:Kansas City Chiefs at Denver Broncos 1985-12-14 (ticket) (crop).jpg|thumb|200px|[[Len Dawson]] led the Chiefs to victory in [[Super Bowl IV]] and was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 1987]]\n\n===Early success===\nThe Texans shared the [[Cotton Bowl (stadium)|Cotton Bowl]] with the NFL's cross-town competition [[Dallas Cowboys]] for three seasons. The Texans were to have exclusive access to the stadium until the NFL put an expansion team, the Dallas Cowboys, there.<ref name=\"AFL Origins\"/> While the team averaged a league-best 24,500 at the Cotton Bowl, the Texans gained less attention due to the AFL's relatively lower profile compared to the NFL.<ref name=\"AFL Origins\"/> In the franchise's first two seasons, the team managed only an 8\u20136 and 6\u20138 record, respectively.<ref name=\"PFR\">{{cite web |title=Kansas City Chiefs Franchise Encyclopedia |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/ |publisher=Pro Football Reference |accessdate=January 11, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090119171848/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/ |archivedate=January 19, 2009}}</ref> In their third season, the Texans strolled to an 11\u20133 record and a berth in the team's first [[American Football League playoffs|American Football League Championship Game]], against the [[Houston Oilers]].<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"PFR\"/> The game was broadcast nationally on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and the Texans defeated the Oilers 20\u201317 in double overtime.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> The game lasted 77 minutes and 54 seconds, which still stands as the longest championship game in professional football history.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/>\n\nIt turned out to be the last game the team would play as the Dallas Texans. Despite competing against a Cowboys team that managed only a 9\u201328\u20133 record in their first three seasons, Hunt decided that the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Metroplex|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]] [[media market]] could not sustain two professional football franchises.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"This Week February 8, 2008\">{{cite news |last=Kuhbander|first=Brad|title=Kuhbander: This Week in Chiefs History |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/02/08/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history34/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC |website=Chiefs.com|date=February 8, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219105414/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/02/08/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history34/|archivedate=February 19, 2008}}</ref> He considered moving the Texans to either [[Atlanta]] or [[Miami]] for the 1963 season.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> However, he was ultimately swayed by an offer from [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] Mayor [[Harold Roe Bartle]].<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"This Week February 8, 2008\"/><ref name=\"Gruver 103\">Gruver, p. 103</ref> Bartle promised to triple the franchise's season ticket sales and expand the seating capacity of [[Municipal Stadium (Kansas City, Missouri)|Municipal Stadium]] to accommodate the team.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"This Week February 8, 2008\"/><ref name=\"Gruver 103\" />\n\nHunt agreed to [[Relocation of professional sports teams|relocate]] the franchise to Kansas City on May 22, 1963, and on May 26 the team was renamed the Kansas City Chiefs.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"This Week February 8, 2008\"/><ref name=\"Gruver 103\" /> Hunt and head coach Hank Stram initially planned to retain the Texans name, but a fan contest determined the new \"Chiefs\" name in honor of Mayor Bartle's nickname that he acquired in his professional role as Scout Executive of the St. Joseph and Kansas City Boy Scout Councils and founder of the Scouting Society, the [[Tribe of Mic-O-Say]].<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"Gruver 103\" />\n\nThe franchise became one of the strongest teams in the now thriving American Football League,<ref name=\"PFHOF\"/> with the most playoff appearances for an AFL team (tied with the [[Oakland Raiders]]), and the most AFL Championships (3).<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> The team's dominance helped Lamar Hunt become a central figure in negotiations with NFL Commissioner [[Pete Rozelle]] to agree on an [[AFL\u2013NFL merger]].<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"Maske, Mark\">Maske, p. 325</ref> In the meetings between the two leagues, a [[Professional American football championship games|merged league championship game]] was agreed to be played in January 1967 following the conclusion of the leagues' respective 1966 seasons. Hunt insisted on calling the game the \"Super Bowl\" after seeing his children playing with a popular toy at the time, a [[Super Ball]].<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"Maske, Mark\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/chi-0701300052jan30,1,233400.story?track=rss&ctrack=1&cset=true |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070202183127/http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/football/bears/chi-0701300052jan30,1,233400.story?track=rss&ctrack=1&cset=true |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 2, 2007 |title=Legends of the Bowl |accessdate=January 31, 2007 |author=Rex W. Huppke |date=January 30, 2007 |work=Chicago Tribune |quote= Lamar Hunt, who died in December, coined the term Super Bowl in the late 1960s after watching his kids play with a Super Ball, the bouncy creation of iconic toy manufacturer Wham-O.}}</ref> While the first few games were designated the \"AFL\u2013NFL World Championship Game\", the Super Bowl name became its officially licensed title in years to come.\n\n{{multiple image\n|align=right\n|direction=horizontal\n|footer=The Chiefs topped the Raiders in the [[1969 American Football League Championship Game|1969 AFL championship game]] (''left'') and went on to defeat the Vikings in Super Bowl IV (''right'')\n|footer_align=left\n|image1=1986 Jeno's Pizza - 49 - Robert Holmes.jpg\n|width1=140\n|image2 =1986 Jeno's Pizza - 50 - Buck Buchanan and Curley Culp.jpg\n|width2=140\n}}\n\nThe Chiefs cruised to an 11\u20132\u20131 record in 1966, and defeated the defending AFL Champion [[Buffalo Bills]] in the AFL Championship Game.<ref name=\"Gruver 167\">Gruver, p. 167</ref> The Chiefs were invited to play the NFL's league champion [[Green Bay Packers]] in [[Super Bowl I|the first AFL\u2013NFL World Championship Game]]. Kansas City and Green Bay played a close game for the first half, but Green Bay took control in the final two quarters, winning the game by a score of 35\u201310.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> The Chiefs lost the game but gained the respect of several Packers opponents following the game.<ref name=\"Gruver 179\">Gruver, p. 179</ref> The Chiefs' inter-league match-up with the Packers was not the last time that they would face an NFL opponent, especially on the championship stage.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> The following August, Kansas City hosted the NFL's [[Chicago Bears]] in the 1967 preseason and won the game 66\u201324.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/>\n\nDespite losing to the division rival Oakland Raiders twice in the regular season in 1969, the two teams met for a third time in the AFL Championship Game where Kansas City won 17\u20137.<ref name=\"PFR\"/> Backup quarterback [[Mike Livingston]] led the team in a six-game winning streak after [[Len Dawson]] suffered a leg injury which kept him out of most of the season's games.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> While getting plenty of help from the club's defense, Dawson returned from the injury and led the Chiefs to [[Super Bowl IV]].<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> Against the NFL champion [[Minnesota Vikings]],<ref name=\"PFHOF\"/> who were [[spread betting|favored]] by 12\u00bd, the Chiefs dominated the game 23\u20137 to claim the team's first Super Bowl championship.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> Dawson was named the game's [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] after completing 12-of-17 passes for 142 yards and one touchdown, with 1 interception.<ref name=\"Dawson\">{{cite web|title=Len Dawson |publisher=Pro Football Reference |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DawsLe00.htm |accessdate=July 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829163503/http://pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DawsLe00.htm |archivedate=August 29, 2008 }}</ref> The following season, the Chiefs and the rest of the American Football League merged with the National Football League after the AFL\u2013NFL merger became official.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> The Chiefs were placed in the [[American Football Conference]]'s [[American Football Conference West Division|West Division]].<ref name=\"PFR\"/>\n\nFrom 1960 to 1969, the Chiefs/Texans won 87 games, which is the most in the 10-year history of the AFL.<ref>One game more than the [[San Diego Chargers seasons|Los Angeles/San Diego Chargers]], [http://pfref.com/tiny/RVKdE Pro-Football-Reference.com: In multiple seasons, from 1960 to 1969, in the regular season, sorted by descending Date.]</ref>\n\nIn 1970, the Chiefs won only seven games in their first season in the NFL and missed the playoffs.<ref name=\"PFR\"/> The following season, the Chiefs tallied a 10\u20133\u20131 record and won the AFC West Division.<ref name=\"History 70s\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs History \u2013 1970s|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/70s/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Chiefs.com|accessdate=December 31, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609052751/http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/70s/|archivedate=June 9, 2008}}</ref> Head coach Hank Stram considered his 1971 Chiefs team as his best, but they failed to capture their championship dominance from 1969.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> Most of the pieces of the team which won Super Bowl IV two years earlier were still in place for the 1971 season.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> The Chiefs tied with the [[Miami Dolphins]] for the best record in the AFC, and both teams met in a [[Christmas Day]] playoff game which the Chiefs lost 27\u201324 in double overtime.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> The Dolphins outlasted the Chiefs with a 37-yard [[Field goal (football)|field goal]].<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> The game surpassed the 1962 AFL Championship Game as the longest ever at 82 minutes and 40 seconds.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> The game was also the final football game at Kansas City's Municipal Stadium.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/>\n\nIn 1972, the Chiefs moved into the newly constructed [[Arrowhead Stadium]] at the [[Truman Sports Complex]] outside of [[CBD-Downtown, Kansas City|Downtown Kansas City]].<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> The team's first game at Arrowhead was against the [[St. Louis Cardinals (NFL)|St. Louis Cardinals]], a preseason game which the Chiefs won 24\u201314.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> Linebacker [[Willie Lanier]] and quarterback Len Dawson won the [[Walter Payton Man of the Year Award|NFL Man of the Year Award]] in 1972 and 1973, respectively.\n\n===Decline===\nThe Chiefs would not return to the [[NFL playoffs|post-season]] for the remainder of the 1970s, and the 1973 season was the team's last winning effort for seven years.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> Hank Stram was fired following a 5\u20139 season in 1974, and many of the Chiefs' future [[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] players would depart by the middle of the decade.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> From 1975 to 1988, the Chiefs had become a team that rarely won which provided Chiefs fans with nothing but futility.<ref name=\"Althaus 97\">Althaus, p. 97</ref><ref name=\"Althaus 101\">Althaus, p. 101</ref> Five head coaches struggled to achieve the same success as Stram, compiling an 81\u2013121\u20131 record.<ref name=\"Althaus 97\" />\n\nIn 1980, Coach Marv Levy cut future Hall of Fame Kicker [[Jan Stenerud]] for little known [[Nick Lowery]], who would become the most accurate kicker in NFL History over the next 14 years. In 1981, running back [[Joe Delaney]] rushed for 1,121 yards and was named the [[National Football League Rookie of the Year|AFC Rookie of the Year]].<ref name=\"History 80s\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs History \u2013 1980s|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/80s/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Chiefs.com|accessdate=December 31, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501122552/http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/80s/|archivedate=May 1, 2008}}</ref> The Chiefs finished the season with a 9\u20137 record and entered the 1982 season with optimism.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/> However, the [[1982 NFL strike|NFL Players Association strike]] curbed the Chiefs' chances of returning to the postseason for the first time in over a decade.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/> The Chiefs tallied a 3\u20136 record<ref name=\"PFR\"/> and in the off-season, Joe Delaney died while trying to save several children from drowning in a pond near his home in Louisiana.<ref name=\"Joe Delaney headed\">{{cite news|title=Joe Delaney headed for Chiefs ring of honor Sunday |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2004/09/23/joe_delaney_headed_for_chiefs_ring_of_honor_sunday/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC |website=Chiefs.com|date=September 23, 2004|accessdate=July 13, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050113113830/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2004/09/23/joe_delaney_headed_for_chiefs_ring_of_honor_sunday/|archivedate=January 13, 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe Chiefs made a mistake in drafting quarterback [[Todd Blackledge]] over future greats such as [[Jim Kelly]] and [[Dan Marino]] in the [[1983 NFL Draft]].<ref name=\"Althaus 167\">Althaus, p. 167</ref><ref name=\"Warrick\">{{cite web |title=Warrick, Klinger fell way short in Cincy |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/news/story?id=3326109 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=April 16, 2008 |accessdate=January 16, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204040120/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/news/story?id=3326109 |archivedate=December 4, 2008}}</ref> Blackledge never started a full season for Kansas City while Kelly and Marino played Hall of Fame careers.<ref name=\"Warrick\"/> While the Chiefs struggled on offense in the 1980s, the Chiefs had a strong defensive unit consisting of Pro Bowlers such as [[Bill Maas]], [[Albert Lewis (American football)|Albert Lewis]], [[Art Still]] and [[Deron Cherry]].<ref name=\"History 80s\"/>\n\n[[John Mackovic]] took over head coaching duties for the 1983 season after [[Marv Levy]] was fired.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/> Over the next four seasons, Mackovic coached the Chiefs to a 30\u201334 record, but took the team to its first post-season appearance in 15 years in the [[NFL playoffs, 1986\u201387|1986 NFL playoffs]].<ref name=\"PFR\"/> They lost to the [[New York Jets]] in the wild-card round.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/> Despite leading the Chiefs to only their third winning season and second playoff appearance since the merger, Mackovic was fired for what Hunt described as a lack of chemistry.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/09/sports/sports-people-mackovic-released.html Mackovic released]. ''New York Times'', January 9, 1987.</ref> [[Frank Gansz]] served as head coach for the next two seasons, but won only eight of 31 games.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/>\n\n===Marty Schottenheimer era===\nOn December 19, 1988, owner Lamar Hunt hired [[Carl Peterson]] as the team's new president, general manager, and chief executive officer. Peterson fired head coach Frank Gansz two weeks after taking over and hired [[Marty Schottenheimer]] as the club's seventh head coach.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/> In the [[1988 NFL Draft|1988]] and [[1989 NFL Draft|1989]] [[NFL Draft]]s, the Chiefs selected both defensive end [[Neil Smith (American football)|Neil Smith]] and linebacker [[Derrick Thomas]], respectively.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/><ref name=\"History 90s\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs History \u2013 1990s |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/90s/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Chiefs.com|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709055422/http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/90s/|archivedate=July 9, 2008}}</ref> The defense that Thomas and Smith anchored in their seven seasons together was a big reason why the Chiefs reached the postseason in six straight years.<ref name=\"Althaus 63\">Althaus, p. 63</ref>\n\nIn Schottenheimer's ten-season tenure as head coach, the Chiefs became a perennial playoff contender, featuring offensive players including [[Steve DeBerg]], [[Christian Okoye]], [[Stephone Paige]] and [[Barry Word]], a strong defense, anchored by Thomas, Smith, Albert Lewis and Deron Cherry, and on special teams, [[Nick Lowery]], then the most accurate kicker in NFL History.<ref name=\"PFHOF\"/> The team recorded a 101\u201358\u20131 record, and clinched seven playoff berths.<ref name=\"Schottenheimer\"/> The Chiefs' 1993 season was the franchise's most successful in 22 years.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> With newly acquired quarterback [[Joe Montana]] and running back [[Marcus Allen]], two former [[Super Bowl]] champions and MVPs, the Chiefs further strengthened their position in the NFL.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> The 11\u20135 Chiefs defeated the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] and [[Houston Oilers]] on their way to the franchise's first [[AFC Championship Game]] appearance against the Buffalo Bills.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> The Chiefs were overwhelmed by the Bills and lost the game by a score of 30\u201313.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> The Chiefs' victory on January 16, 1994, against the Oilers remained the franchise's last post-season victory for 21 years until their 30\u20130 victory over the Houston Texans on January 9, 2016.\n\nIn the [[NFL playoffs, 1995\u201396|1995 NFL playoffs]], the 13\u20133 Chiefs hosted the [[Indianapolis Colts]] in a cold, damp late afternoon game at Arrowhead Stadium.<ref name=\"PFR\"/><ref name=\"History 90s\"/> Kansas City lost the game 10\u20137 against the underdog Colts, after [[placekicker|kicker]] [[Lin Elliot]] missed three field goal attempts and quarterback Steve Bono threw three interceptions.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> The Chiefs selected [[tight end]] [[Tony Gonzalez]] with the 13th overall selection in the [[1997 NFL Draft]], a move which some considered to be a gamble being that Gonzalez was primarily a [[basketball]] player at [[University of California, Berkeley|California]]. During a 1997 season full of injuries to starting quarterback [[Elvis Grbac]], backup quarterback [[Rich Gannon]] took the reins of the Chiefs' offense as the team headed to another 13\u20133 season.<ref name=\"PFR\"/><ref name=\"History 90s\"/> Head coach Marty Schottenheimer chose Grbac to start the playoff game against the [[Denver Broncos]] despite Gannon's successes in previous weeks.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> Grbac's production in the game was lacking, and the Chiefs lost to the Broncos 14\u201310.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> Denver went on to capture their fifth AFC Championship by defeating Pittsburgh, and then defeated the Green Bay Packers in [[Super Bowl XXXII]]. Coach Schottenheimer announced his resignation from the Chiefs following the 1998 season.\n\n===1999\u20132006===\nFollowing Schottenheimer's resignation, defensive coordinator [[Gunther Cunningham]] took over coaching duties for the next two seasons, compiling a 16\u201316 record.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> By the end of the Chiefs' decade of regular-season dominance, Gannon had signed with the Oakland Raiders, Neil Smith signed with the [[Denver Broncos]], and Derrick Thomas was paralyzed from a car accident on January 23, 2000.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> Thomas died from complications of his injury weeks later.<ref name=\"History 90s\"/> After allegedly reading online that he would be relieved of duties, head coach Gunther Cunningham was fired.<ref name=\"Chiefs name Gunther\">{{cite news |first=Doug|last=Tucker |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/chiefs/2004-01-20-cunningham_x.htm|title=Chiefs name Gunther Cunningham defensive coordinator|work=USA Today|date=January 20, 2004 |accessdate=July 9, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"History 2000s\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs History \u2013 2000s|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/2000s/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609095508/http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/2000s/|archivedate=June 9, 2008}}</ref>\n[[File:Tony Gonzalez at 2005 Pro Bowl 050213-N-3019M-002.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Tony Gonzalez]] at the [[2005 Pro Bowl]]]]\n[[File:Priest Holmes speaks with soldiers CROPPED.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Priest Holmes]] became one of the league's top backs in the early 2000s]]\nLooking to change the Chiefs' game plan which relied on a tough defensive strategy for the past decade, Carl Peterson contacted [[Dick Vermeil]] about the Chiefs' head coaching vacancy for the 2001 season.<ref name=\"Chiefs name Gunther\"/> Vermeil previously led the [[St. Louis Rams]] to a victory in [[Super Bowl XXXIV]].<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Vermeil was hired on January 12. The Chiefs then traded a first-round draft pick in the [[2001 NFL Draft]] to St. Louis for quarterback [[Trent Green]] and signed free agent running back [[Priest Holmes]] to be the team's cornerstones on offense.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/>\n\nIn 2003, Kansas City began the season with nine consecutive victories, a franchise record.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> They finished the season with a 13\u20133 record and the team's offense led the NFL in several categories under the direction of USA Today's Offensive Coach of the Year honoree, Al Saunders.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Running back [[Priest Holmes]] surpassed [[Marshall Faulk]]'s single-season touchdown record by scoring his 27th rushing touchdown against the [[Chicago Bears]] in the team's regular season finale.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/><ref name=\"Althaus 65\">Althaus, p. 65</ref> The team clinched the second seed in the [[2003\u201304 NFL playoffs|2004 NFL playoffs]] and hosted the [[Indianapolis Colts]] in the AFC Divisional Playoffs.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> In a game where neither team punted, the Chiefs lost the shoot-out 38\u201331.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> It was the third time in nine seasons that the Chiefs went 8\u20130 at home in the regular season, only to lose their post-season opener at Arrowhead.\n\nAfter a disappointing 7\u20139 record in 2004, the 2005 Chiefs finished with a 10\u20136 record but no playoff berth.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> They were the fourth team since 1990 to miss the playoffs with a 10\u20136 record.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Running back [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] started in place of the injured Priest Holmes and rushed for 1,750 yards in only nine starts.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Prior to the Chiefs' final game of the season, head coach Dick Vermeil announced his retirement.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> The Chiefs won the game 37\u20133 over the playoff-bound [[Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/>\n\n[[File:Huard and Croyle.JPG|right|thumb|[[Damon Huard]] (left) and [[Brodie Croyle]] (right) both served as the Chiefs' starting quarterback after [[Trent Green]]'s departure]]\nWithin two weeks of Vermeil's resignation, the Chiefs returned to their defensive roots with the selection of its next head coach.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> The team introduced [[Herman Edwards]], a former Chiefs scout and head coach of the New York Jets, as the team's tenth head coach after trading a fourth-round selection in the [[2006 NFL Draft]] to the Jets.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Quarterback Trent Green suffered a severe concussion in the team's season opener to the Cincinnati Bengals which left him out of play for eight weeks.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Backup quarterback [[Damon Huard]] took over in Green's absence and led the Chiefs to a 5\u20133 record.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/>\n\nKansas City was awarded a [[NFL on Thanksgiving Day|Thanksgiving Day game]] against the Denver Broncos in response to owner Lamar Hunt's lobbying for a third Thanksgiving Day game.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> The Chiefs defeated the Broncos 19\u201310 in the first Thanksgiving Day game in Kansas City since 1969.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Hunt was hospitalized at the time of the game and died weeks later on December 13 due to complications with [[prostate cancer]].<ref name=\"Maske, Mark\" /><ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> The Chiefs honored their owner for the remainder of the season, as did the rest of the league.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/>\n\n[[File:061231Jaguars-Chiefs.jpg|thumb|left|By defeating the [[Jacksonville Jaguars|Jaguars]] on December 31, 2006, the Chiefs clinched a playoff berth after multiple other teams lost throughout the day]]\nTrent Green returned in the middle of the season, but struggled in the final stretch,<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> and running back Larry Johnson set an NFL record with 416 carries in a season.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Kansas City managed to clinch their first [[2006\u201307 NFL playoffs|playoff berth]] in three seasons with a 9\u20137 record and a bizarre sequence of six losses from other AFC teams on New Year's Eve, culminating with a Broncos loss to the 49ers.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> The Indianapolis Colts hosted the Chiefs in the Wild Card playoffs and defeated Kansas City 23\u20138.\n\n===2007\u20132012, second decline===\n[[File:Larry Johnson Chiefs.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] in 2006]]\nIn 2007, [[Trent Green]] was traded to the Miami Dolphins<ref name=\"Green goes to Dolphins\">{{cite web |title=Green goes to Dolphins from Chiefs in trade |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2894600 |last=Pasquarelli |first=Len |date=June 5, 2007 |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010134524/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2894600 |archivedate=October 10, 2007}}</ref> leaving the door open for either Damon Huard or [[Brodie Croyle]] to become the new starting quarterback.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> After starting the season with a 4\u20133 record, the Chiefs lost the remaining nine games when running back Larry Johnson suffered a season-ending foot injury and the quarterback position lacked stability with Huard and Croyle.<ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> Despite the team's 4\u201312 record, tight end [[Tony Gonzalez]] broke [[Shannon Sharpe]]'s NFL record for touchdowns at the position (63) and [[defensive end]] [[Jared Allen]] led the NFL in [[quarterback sacks]] with 15.5.<ref name=\"PFR\"/>\n\nThe Chiefs began their 2008 season with the youngest team in the NFL.<ref name=\"Interesting list\">{{cite web |title=Interesting list of suitors for Hall |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=3687123&name=clayton_john |last=Clayton |first=John |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 6, 2008 |accessdate=November 14, 2008}}</ref> The starting lineup had an average of 25.5 years of age.<ref name=\"Interesting list\"/> By releasing several veteran players such as cornerback [[Ty Law]] and wide receiver [[Eddie Kennison]] and trading defensive end Jared Allen,<ref name=\"KC trades DE Jared Allen\">{{cite news|title=KC trades DE Jared Allen to Minnesota for multiple draft choices |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/04/23/kc_trades_de_jared_allen_to_minnesota_for_multiple_draft_choices/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Chiefs.com|date=April 23, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609094224/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/04/23/kc_trades_de_jared_allen_to_minnesota_for_multiple_draft_choices/|archivedate=June 9, 2008}}</ref> the Chiefs began a youth movement.<ref name=\"Interesting list\"/><ref name=\"Thigpen to start\">{{cite news|title=Chiefs QB Thigpen to start vs. Falcons|agency=Associated Press|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3593861|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=September 17, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919151055/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3593861|archivedate=September 19, 2008 }}</ref> The Chiefs had a league-high thirteen selections in the [[2008 NFL Draft]] and chose defensive tackle [[Glenn Dorsey]] and offensive lineman [[Branden Albert]] in the first round. Analysts quickly called Kansas City's selections as the best of the entire draft.<ref name=\"KC trades DE Jared Allen\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs' Day 1\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs' Day 1 plan comes together with Dorsey, others|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/columns/story?columnist=clayton_john&id=3369696|publisher=ESPN.com|date=April 26, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024071047/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/columns/story?columnist=clayton_john&id=3369696|archivedate=October 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Draft yields\">{{cite web|title=Draft yields quantity, and plenty of quality, for Chiefs|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/columns/story?columnist=kiper_jr_mel&id=3357479|publisher=ESPN.com|date=April 27, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022222226/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/columns/story?columnist=kiper_jr_mel&id=3357479|archivedate=October 22, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Several '08\">{{cite web|title=Several '08 picks should make immediate impact|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=williamson_bill&id=3448409|last=Williamson|first=Bill|publisher=ESPN.com|date=June 18, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080804091600/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=williamson_bill&id=3448409|archivedate=August 4, 2008 }}</ref> Entering the season, the Chiefs were unsure if injury-prone quarterback Brodie Croyle, who was the incumbent starter, could be their quarterback in the long-term.<ref name=\"Several '08\"/> Croyle was injured in the team's first game of the season and Damon Huard started in Croyle's absence.<ref name=\"Croyle out\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80aa747b&template=with-video&confirm=true|title=Chiefs QB Croyle out for this week|agency=Associated Press|date=September 8, 2008|publisher=NFL.com|accessdate=September 17, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910235140/http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80aa747b&template=with-video&confirm=true|archivedate=September 10, 2008}}</ref> [[Tyler Thigpen]] become the third Chiefs starting quarterback in as many games for a start against the [[Atlanta Falcons]].<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|title=Chiefs QB Thigpen to start vs. Falcons|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3593861|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=September 17, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919151055/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3593861|archivedate=September 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Falcons back\"/> After a poor performance by Thigpen, in which he threw three interceptions against the Falcons defense,<ref name=\"Falcons back\"/> Huard was retained as the starting quarterback.<ref name=\"Huard will start\">{{cite news|title=Huard will start at quarterback Sunday for Kansas City|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80b168a8&template=with-video&confirm=true|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NFL.com|date=September 22, 2008|accessdate=November 14, 2008}}</ref> The Chiefs struggled off the field as much as on as tight end Tony Gonzalez demanded a trade and running back Larry Johnson was involved in legal trouble.<ref name=\"Johnson under\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs' Johnson under investigation for latest incident involving a woman|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3654308|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 20, 2008|accessdate=October 21, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023102659/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3654308|archivedate=October 23, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"spitting in woman's face\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs willing\">{{cite web|title=Source: Chiefs willing to listen to offers for record-setting TE Gonzalez|last=Smith|first=Michael|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3638551|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 12, 2008|accessdate=October 21, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020232347/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3638551|archivedate=October 20, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Gonzalez tells\">{{cite web|title=Gonzalez tells teammates he's not bitter about failed trade request|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3645516|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 16, 2008|accessdate=October 21, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081018172018/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3645516|archivedate=October 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\nCroyle returned for the Chiefs' game against the Tennessee Titans, but both he and Damon Huard suffered season-ending injuries in the game.<ref name=\"Croyle sprains\">{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Chiefs QB Croyle sprains right knee, done for the season|publisher=ESPN.com|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3652130|date=October 19, 2008|accessdate=October 19, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022110109/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3652130|archivedate=October 22, 2008 }}</ref> The Chiefs reorganized their offense to a new [[spread offense]] game plan focused around Tyler Thigpen.<ref name=\"Thigpen to start\"/><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|title=Chiefs QB Croyle out for this week|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80aa747b&template=with-video&confirm=true|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NFL.com|date=September 8, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910235140/http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80aa747b&template=with-video&confirm=true|archivedate=September 10, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\">{{cite news|last=Rand|first=Jonathan|title=Breaking the Mold|url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/11/13/breaking_the_mold/|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=Chiefs.com|date=November 13, 2008|accessdate=November 14, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110191420/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/11/13/breaking_the_mold/|archivedate=January 10, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Spread changes\">{{cite web|title=Spread changes options for Chiefs|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?id=3717080|last=Chadiha|first=Jeffri|publisher=ESPN.com|date=November 21, 2008|accessdate=November 26, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025084224/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?id=3717080|archivedate=October 25, 2012 }}</ref> The Chiefs' new offense was implemented to help Thigpen play to the best of his abilities and also following the absence of Larry Johnson, who was suspended for his off-field conduct.<ref name=\"spitting in woman's face\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs' Johnson charged for spitting in woman's face, won't play for now|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3667069|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 28, 2008|accessdate=October 28, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030081901/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3667069|archivedate=October 30, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\"/><ref name=\"Spread changes\"/><ref name=Johnson>{{cite web|title=Source: Johnson's discipline in response to pattern of behavior|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3647097|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 18, 2008|accessdate=October 21, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019114358/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3647097|archivedate=October 19, 2008}}</ref> The Chiefs made a huge gamble by using the spread offense, as most in the NFL believe that it cannot work in professional football, and also head coach Herman Edwards was traditionally in favor of more conservative, run-oriented game plans.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/>\n\n[[File:Alleman Blocking.jpg|thumb|right|The Chiefs hosting the [[Buffalo Bills]] in 2009; Quarterback [[Matt Cassel]], wearing #7]]\nThe 2008 season ended with a franchise worst 2\u201314 record, where the team suffered historic blowout defeats nearly week-in and week-out.<ref name=\"PFR\"/><ref name=\"Falcons back\">{{cite news|title=Falcons back on track after victory over winless Chiefs|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29560&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG3|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NFL.com|date=September 21, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211161602/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29560&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG3|archivedate=December 11, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Titans extend\">{{cite news|title=Titans extend winning streak as Chiefs lose game, Croyle|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29621&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG7&override=true|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NFL.com|date=October 19, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023113330/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29621&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG7&override=true|archivedate=October 23, 2008 }}</ref> a 34\u20130 shut-out to the [[Carolina Panthers]],<ref name=\"Williams' career-best\">{{cite news|title=Williams' career-best game helps Panthers blank Chiefs|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29590&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG5|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NFL.com|date=October 5, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211052706/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29590&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2008&week=REG5|archivedate=December 11, 2008 }}</ref> and allowed a franchise-high 54 points against the Buffalo Bills.<ref name=\"Edwards helps Bills\">{{cite news|title=Edwards helps Bills score most against Chiefs in history|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281123012|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=November 23, 2008|accessdate=November 23, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206232353/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281123012|archivedate=December 6, 2008 }}</ref> The team's general manager, chief executive officer, and team president Carl Peterson resigned at the end of the season,<ref name=\"Chiefs GM Peterson\">{{cite news|title=Chiefs GM Peterson to step down at end of season|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3771725|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=December 15, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217064716/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3771725|archivedate=December 17, 2008 }}</ref> and former [[New England Patriots]] vice president of player personnel [[Scott Pioli]] was hired as his replacement for 2009.<ref name=\"Pioli to join\">{{cite web|title=Scott Pioli to join Kansas City Chiefs|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3830515|publisher=ESPN.com|date=January 13, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090120005016/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3830515|archivedate=January 20, 2009 }}</ref>\n[[File:Dwayne Bowe.JPG|thumb|left|[[Dwayne Bowe]]]]\nOn January 23, 2009, Herman Edwards was fired as head coach,<ref name=\"Chiefs fire Edwards\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs fire Edwards; Shanahan next?|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3855917|publisher=ESPN.com|date=January 23, 2009|accessdate=January 23, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130095804/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3855917|archivedate=January 30, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Edwards relieved\">{{cite web|title=Herm Edwards relieved of duties as Chiefs head coach |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/01/23/herm_edwards_relieved_of_duties_as_chiefs_head_coach/ |date=January 23, 2009 |accessdate=January 23, 2009 |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126010523/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/01/23/herm_edwards_relieved_of_duties_as_chiefs_head_coach |archivedate=January 26, 2009}}</ref> and two weeks later [[Todd Haley]] signed a four-year contract to become Edwards' successor.<ref name=\"Haley named\">{{cite web|title=Todd Haley named Kansas City Chiefs head coach |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=February 6, 2009 |accessdate=February 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090209090923/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/06/todd_haley_named_kansas_city_chiefs_head_coach |archivedate=February 9, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\">{{cite news|title=Chiefs hire Cardinals offensive coordinator Haley as coach|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80e9b58a&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true|agency=Associated Press|date=February 6, 2009|accessdate=February 6, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207104632/http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80e9b58a&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true|archivedate=February 7, 2009 }}</ref> Haley had a background with Pioli, which made him an attractive hire for Pioli's first coach in Kansas City.\n\nIn April 2009, [[Tony Gonzalez]] was traded to the [[Atlanta Falcons]] after failed trade attempts over the previous two seasons.<ref name=\"Chiefs trade Gonzalez\">{{cite news|title=Chiefs trade Gonzalez for 2010 draft pick|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4092471|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=April 23, 2009|accessdate=June 7, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426060634/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4092471|archivedate=April 26, 2009 }}</ref> Notably, head coach Todd Haley fired offensive coordinator [[Chan Gailey]] just weeks before the start of the 2009 season and chose to take on the coordinator duties himself. Throughout 2009 the Chiefs acquired veterans to supplement the Chiefs' young talent including [[Matt Cassel]], [[Mike Vrabel]], [[Bobby Engram]], [[Mike Brown (American football)|Mike Brown]], [[Chris Chambers]], and [[Andy Alleman]].<ref name=\"Chiefs complete\">{{cite news|title=Chiefs complete trade for Cassel|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/02/28/chiefs.trade.for.cassel/index.html|last=King|first=Peter|work=Sports Illustrated|date=February 28, 2009|accessdate=February 28, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304141840/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/02/28/chiefs.trade.for.cassel/index.html|archivedate=March 4, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Cassel, Vrabel\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs acquire QB Matt Cassel, LB Mike Vrabel in trade with Patriots |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/28/chiefs_acquire_qb_matt_cassel_lb_mike_vrabel_in_trade_with_patriots/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=February 28, 2009 |accessdate=February 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304002108/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/28/chiefs_acquire_qb_matt_cassel_lb_mike_vrabel_in_trade_with_patriots |archivedate=March 4, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs claim Chambers\">{{cite news|title=Chiefs claim Chambers|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4620312|publisher=ESPN.com|agency=Associated Press|date=November 3, 2009|accessdate=November 3, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107000805/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=4620312|archivedate=November 7, 2009 }}</ref> The team finished with a 4\u201312 record, just a two-game improvement upon their record from the 2008 season.\n\nFor the 2010 season, the Chiefs made significant hires for their coaching staff, bringing on former Patriots assistant coaches [[Charlie Weis]] and [[Romeo Crennel]] to coach the offense and defense, respectively. The coaching additions proved to be very successful, as the Chiefs would go on to secure their first AFC West title since 2003. Their ten victories in the 2010 season combined for as many as the team had won in their previous three seasons combined.\n\nOn January 9, 2011, the Chiefs lost their home Wild Card playoff game to the Baltimore Ravens 30\u20137. Six players were chosen for the Pro Bowl: Dwayne Bowe, [[Jamaal Charles]], Brian Waters, Tamba Hali, Matt Cassel, and rookie safety Eric Berry. Jamaal Charles won the FEDEX ground player of the year award and Dwayne Bowe led the NFL in Touchdown Receptions.\n\nFor their first pick in the [[2011 NFL draft]], and 26th overall, the team selected [[Jon Baldwin|Jonathan Baldwin]], [[Wide Receiver]] from [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pitt]]. After a poor start, Haley was relieved of duties as Head Coach on December 12. Clark Hunt made note of \"bright spots at different points this season\", but felt that overall the Chiefs were not progressing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/HALEY-RELIEVED-OF-DUTIES/9f2d029b-c450-48cb-9791-8038582a3270|title=HALEY RELIEVED OF DUTIES|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107051055/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/HALEY-RELIEVED-OF-DUTIES/9f2d029b-c450-48cb-9791-8038582a3270|archivedate=January 7, 2012|access-date=December 12, 2011}}</ref> The highest point of the 2011 season was an upset win against the Packers, who at that time, were undefeated with a 13\u20130 record.\n\nThe 2012 Chiefs became the first team since the 1929 [[Buffalo (1920s NFL teams)|Buffalo Bisons]] to not lead in regulation through any of their first nine games. The Chiefs tied their franchise worst record of 2\u201314 and clinched the No. 1 overall pick in the [[2013 NFL Draft]]. It is the first time since the merger they have held the first overall pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/blog/rob-rang/21474615/updated-2013-nfl-draft-order|title=2013 NFL Draft order set|work=CBSSports.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525030513/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/blog/rob-rang/21474615/updated-2013-nfl-draft-order|archivedate=May 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Andy Reid, John Dorsey era===\nFollowing the 2012 season, the Chiefs fired head coach [[Romeo Crennel]] and general manager [[Scott Pioli]]. Former [[Philadelphia Eagles]] head coach [[Andy Reid]] was brought in as head coach to work with new general manager [[John Dorsey (American football)|John Dorsey]], a former [[Green Bay Packers]] head scout.\n[[File:Andy reid 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|175px|Coach [[Andy Reid]] in 2018]]\nThe Chiefs acquired quarterback [[Alex Smith]] from the [[San Francisco 49ers]] for the Chiefs' second-round pick, 34th overall, in the 2013 draft and a conditional pick in 2014 draft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9044991/san-francisco-49ers-announce-trade-alex-smith-kansas-city-chiefs |author=Bill Williamson |title=Niners announce Alex Smith trade |publisher=espn.com |date=March 12, 2013 |accessdate=April 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315094738/http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9044991/san-francisco-49ers-announce-trade-alex-smith-kansas-city-chiefs |archivedate=March 15, 2013  }}</ref> Matt Cassel was released shortly after. The Chiefs selected [[Eric Fisher (American football)|Eric Fisher]] with the first overall pick of the [[2013 NFL Draft]].\n\nThe Chiefs started 9\u20130 for the second time in team history. They would lead their wildcard game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]] 38\u201310 shortly after halftime, but they would collapse late and lose, 45\u201344.\n\nIn 2014, the Chiefs attempted to make the playoffs for the second straight season for the first time since 1995, however, they finished 9\u20137 and were eliminated in Week 17.\n\nAfter a promising win for the Chiefs against Houston in Week 1, Kansas City went on a five-game losing streak culminating in a 16\u201310 loss to Minnesota and the loss of Jamaal Charles to a torn ACL. However, they managed one of the most improbable season comebacks in the NFL and won ten straight to improve their record from 1\u20135 to 11\u20135. The team clinched a playoff berth after a 17\u201313 win over Cleveland in Week 16 to become only the second NFL team to do so after the merger.{{clarify|date=February 2016}}\n\nThe streak achieved by the Chiefs broke a franchise record for 9 straight (2003, 2013) and second 9 plus game win streak under Reid. After a Week 17 win over Oakland 23\u201317, the Chiefs achieved their longest winning streak in franchise history at ten games. They qualified for the playoffs, playing in the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs|2015 AFC Wild-Card playoff game]], held at [[NRG Stadium]] in [[Houston|Houston, Texas]] on January 9, 2016. The Chiefs defeated the [[Houston Texans]] 30\u20130 to earn their first [[National Football League playoffs|NFL playoff]] win in 23 seasons, dating back to the [[1993\u201394 NFL playoffs]], a win that also came in Houston. The Chiefs' Wild-Card playoff victory ended what was at the time the third-longest [[List of NFL franchise post-season droughts|drought]] in the NFL, and it also ended a then NFL record eight-game playoff losing streak.<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Associated Press]]|title=Kansas City Chiefs dominate Texans in Houston|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2016010900/2015/POST18/chiefs@texans#cat-post-recap-full-story|publisher=National Football League|date=January 9, 2016|accessdate=January 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119214232/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2016010900/2015/POST18/chiefs%40texans#cat-post-recap-full-story|archivedate=January 19, 2016}}</ref> Riddled with injuries, they were defeated by the New England Patriots 27\u201320 in the AFC Divisional Round.\n\nAfter facing a 24\u20133 deficit with six minutes left in the 3rd quarter, the Chiefs engineered a 33\u201327 comeback win against the [[San Diego Chargers]] ending with a two-yard touchdown run by Alex Smith in overtime to give the Chiefs their largest regular season comeback to start the season at 1\u20130.\n\nOn [[National Football League Christmas games|Christmas Day]], the Chiefs defeated the [[Denver Broncos]] 33\u201310 to give Kansas City their tenth straight win against divisional opponents.\n\nOn January 1, 2017, the Chiefs clinched the AFC West and the second seed going into the playoffs that year. They clinched the 2nd seed in the AFC but fell to the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] 18\u201316 as [[Chris Boswell]] hit 6 field goals.\n\nThe Chiefs finished the year with a 10\u20136 record, and won the AFC West. This was the first time in Chiefs history to win the AFC West in back to back years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chiefs top Dolphins, clinch back-to-back division titles for first time in franchise history|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2017/12/24/chiefs-top-dolphins-clinch-back-to-back-division-titles-for-first-time-in-franchise-history/|publisher=Missouri net|accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref> In the Wild Card round the Chiefs lost a tight game to the [[Tennessee Titans]] 22\u201321, allowing [[Derrick Henry]] to rush for 156 yards. The loss extended their NFL record for most consecutive home playoff losses to six.<ref>{{cite web|title=Didn't think the Chiefs' miserable playoff history could get worse? Well, it did|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/didnt-think-chiefs-miserable-playoff-history-get-worse-well-005155220.html|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The game marked the end of Alex Smith's five-year tenure with the Chiefs, as he was traded to the Washington Redskins a few weeks later.\n\n===Patrick Mahomes era, second Super Bowl win===\n[[File:Patrick Mahomes II.JPG|right|thumb|Patrick Mahomes, the Chiefs starting quarterback since 2018]]\nThe Chiefs began the 2018 season with first-year starter [[Patrick Mahomes]] as their quarterback and finished the regular season with a record of 12\u20134, clinching the AFC West for the third year in a row and the AFC's top seed. This included victories over division rivals [[Los Angeles Chargers]], [[Oakland Raiders]] and [[Denver Broncos]] (twice), along with important conference victories over the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], [[Cincinnati Bengals]], and [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]. Their first loss of the season came at the hands of the New England Patriots with a last-second field goal. In their second loss of the season against the [[Los Angeles Rams]] 51\u201354, the Kansas City Chiefs made history by becoming the first NFL team to lose a game after scoring more than 50 points. Mahomes finished the season with 5,097 yards and 50 touchdowns, both team records. He became the 11th quarterback to throw for 5,000 yards and the 3rd to throw for 50 touchdowns. He joined Peyton Manning as only the 2nd player in NFL history to throw for 5,000 yards and 50 touchdowns. For his performance during the season, he was named [[Associated Press NFL Most Valuable Player Award|AP NFL MVP]], the first Chief to win the award.\n\nIn the AFC Divisional round on January 12, 2019, the Chiefs defeated the [[Indianapolis Colts]] 31\u201313 to move on to the AFC Championship Game. This marked the Chiefs' first playoff win in Arrowhead Stadium in 25 years. This also enabled the Chiefs to host the AFC Championship Game for the first time ever. However, the following week, Kansas City's bid for its first Super Bowl berth in 49 years ended with a 31\u201337 overtime loss to the [[New England Patriots]].\n\nThe Chiefs finished the [[2019 NFL season|2019 regular season]] with a 12\u20134 record, winning the [[AFC West]] division title, and the AFC's second seed behind the [[Baltimore Ravens]]. The Chiefs defeated the [[Houston Texans]] 51\u201331 in the AFC Divisional Game after falling behind 24\u20130 at the start of the second quarter with Mahomes throwing for five touchdowns. The Chiefs hosted their second AFC Championship game in consecutive years facing the sixth-seed [[Tennessee Titans]]. The Chiefs then defeated the Titans 35\u201324 and advanced to [[Super Bowl LIV]]. This marked their first appearance in a Super Bowl since [[Super Bowl IV]], 50 years earlier. \n\nOn February 2, 2020, in [[Hard Rock Stadium]] in [[Miami Gardens]], [[Florida]], the Chiefs played [[Super Bowl LIV]], against the NFC top seed, the [[San Francisco 49ers]]. With the game tied at 10 points each at halftime, Mahomes threw 2 interceptions in the 3rd quarter, which enabled the 49ers to take a 20\u201310 lead to the fourth quarter. However, the Chiefs advanced down field, and Mahomes rebounded big-time, throwing 2 touchdowns, to [[Travis Kelce]] and [[Damien Williams]], respectively. With a 24\u201320 lead with under three minutes remaining, Williams had his second touchdown of the night, a 38-yard run, and the Chiefs lead 31\u201320. The game was sealed with a [[Jimmy Garoppolo]] interception with under a minute remaining. This marked the first time in NFL post-season history that a team faced 10 point deficits in 3 straight games, and won all 3 by 10 or more points. Patrick Mahomes won the [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award]]. This was the teams' first championship since 1969, and their first since the [[AFL-NFL Merger]].\n\n==Championships==\nThe Chiefs have won a total of five combined Super Bowl Championships and pre-Super Bowl AFL Championships.\n\n===Super Bowl Championships===\n{| cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Year\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Coach\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Super Bowl\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Location\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Opponent\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Score\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|MVP\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Record\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 1969 || [[Hank Stram]] || [[Super Bowl IV|IV]] || [[New Orleans|New Orleans, LA]] || [[1969 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] || 23\u20137 || QB [[Len Dawson]] || 11\u20133\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 2019 || [[Andy Reid]] || [[Super Bowl LIV|LIV]] || [[Miami|Miami, FL]] || [[2019 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] || 31\u201320 || QB [[Patrick Mahomes]] ||  12\u20134\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center; {{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"\n| colspan=\"7\"|'''Total Super Bowl championships won:'''\n| colspan=\"1\"|'''2'''\n|}\n\n===American Football League Championships===\n{| cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Year\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Coach\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Game\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Location\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Opponent\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Score\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Record\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 1962 || [[Hank Stram]] || [[1962 American Football League Championship Game|1962 AFL Championship Game]] || [[Houston|Houston, TX]] || [[1962 Houston Oilers season|Houston Oilers]] || 20\u201317 || 12\u20133\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 1966 || [[Hank Stram]] || [[1966 American Football League Championship Game|1966 AFL Championship Game]] || [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo, NY]] || [[1966 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] || 31\u20137 || 12\u20132\u20131\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 1969 || [[Hank Stram]] || [[1969 American Football League Championship Game|1969 AFL Championship Game]] || [[Oakland|Oakland, CA]] || [[1969 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]] || 17-7 || 12\u20133\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center; {{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"\n| colspan=\"6\"|'''Total AFL championships won:'''\n| colspan=\"1\"|'''3'''\n|}\n\n===American Football Conference Championships===\n{| cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Year\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Coach\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Location\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Opponent\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Score\n! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"|Record\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| 2019 || [[Andy Reid]] || [[Kansas City, MO]] || [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] || 35\u201324 || 15\u20134\n|- style=\"text-align:center; {{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}};\"\n| colspan=\"5\"|'''Total AFC championships won:'''\n| colspan=\"1\"|'''1'''\n|}\n\n==Logos and uniforms==\n{{Main|Logos and uniforms of the Kansas City Chiefs}}\nWhen the Texans began playing in 1960, the team's logo consisted of the state of [[Texas]] in white with a yellow star marking the location of the city of Dallas. Originally, Hunt chose [[Columbia blue]] and [[Orange (colour)|orange]] for the Texans' uniforms, but [[Bud Adams]] chose Columbia blue and scarlet for his [[Houston Oilers]] franchise.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" /> Hunt reverted to red and gold for the Texans' uniforms, which even after the team relocated to Kansas City, remain as the franchise's colors to this day.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" />\n\nThe state of Texas on the team's helmet was replaced by an [[arrowhead]] design originally sketched by Lamar Hunt on a napkin.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" /> Hunt's inspiration for the interlocking \"KC\" design was the \"SF\" inside of an oval on the [[San Francisco 49ers]] helmets.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" /> Unlike the 49ers' logo, Kansas City's overlapping initials appear inside a white arrowhead instead of an oval and are surrounded by a thin black outline.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" /> From 1960 to 1973, the Chiefs had grey facemask bars on their helmets, but changed to white facemasks in 1974, making them one of the first teams (alongside the San Diego Chargers, who introduced a yellow facemask that same year) in the NFL to use a non-gray facemask.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" />\n\nThe Chiefs' uniform design has essentially remained the same throughout the club's history.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" /> It consists of a red helmet, and either red or white jerseys with the opposite color numbers and names.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" /> White pants were used with both jerseys from 1960 to 1967 and 1989 to 1999.<ref name=\"Uniform History\" /> Beginning in 2009, during the Pioli/Haley era, the team has alternated between white and red pants for road games during the season. Prior to September 15, 2013, the Chiefs always wore white pants with their red jerseys. The Chiefs have never worn an alternate jersey in a game, although custom jerseys are sold for retail.\n\nThe Chiefs wore their white jerseys with white pants at home for the 2006 season opener against the Cincinnati Bengals. The logic behind the uniform selection that day was that the Bengals would be forced to wear their black uniforms on a day that forecasted for steamy temperatures.<ref>Ferrin, Reid. (July 31, 2007) [http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-1/RIVER-FALLS-WRAP-DAY-SIX/45813C34-7DF7-4CA4-AAD6-05E143A9CBAA River Falls Wrap: Day Six] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110220040942/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-1/RIVER-FALLS-WRAP-DAY-SIX/45813C34-7DF7-4CA4-AAD6-05E143A9CBAA |date=February 20, 2011 }}. Kcchiefs.com. Retrieved on July 29, 2013.</ref> The only other time the Chiefs wore white at home was throughout the [[1980 Kansas City Chiefs season|1980 season]] under [[Marv Levy]].\n\nIn 2007, the Kansas City Chiefs honored Lamar Hunt and the AFL with a special patch.<ref name=\"patch\">{{cite web|title=Lamar Hunt patch becomes a permanent part of the Chiefs' uniform |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/01/31/lamar_hunt_patch_becomes_a_permanent_part_of_the_chiefs_uniform/|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|date=January 28, 2008|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609003429/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/01/31/lamar_hunt_patch_becomes_a_permanent_part_of_the_chiefs_uniform/ |archivedate=June 9, 2008}}</ref> It features the AFL's logo from the 1960s with Hunt's \"LH\" initials inside the football.<ref name=\"patch\"/> In 2008, the patch became permanently affixed to the left chest of both Kansas City's home and away jerseys.<ref name=\"patch\"/>\n\nIn select games for the 2009 season, the Chiefs, as well as the other founding teams of the [[American Football League]], wore \"throwback\" uniforms to celebrate the AFL's 50th anniversary.<ref name=\"Chiefs to unveil\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs to unveil \"throwback\" AFL uniforms in 2009 |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/24/chiefs_to_unveil_throwback_afl_uniforms_in_2009/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=March 24, 2009 |accessdate=March 24, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327110604/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/24/chiefs_to_unveil_throwback_afl_uniforms_in_2009 |archivedate=March 27, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nFor the first time in team history, the Chiefs wore their red jersey with red pants forming an all red combo in their home opener against the Dallas Cowboys on September 15, 2013. Their all red uniforms are now an official uniform combination and has been used multiple times since. It is commonly used for prime time games at home. The all-red look also served as the basis for the Chiefs' [[NFL Color Rush|Color Rush]] design.\n\n==Arrowhead Stadium==\n{{Further|Arrowhead Stadium}}\n[[File:Arrowhead Stadium 2010.JPG|left|thumb|[[Arrowhead Stadium]] upon completion of renovations, July 2010]]\nArrowhead Stadium has been the Chiefs' home field since 1972 and has a capacity of 76,416,<ref name=\"seating\">{{cite web |title= Arrowhead Stadium |url= http://www.kcchiefs.com/arrowhead/ |publisher= Kansas City Chiefs |accessdate= September 14, 2009 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090830024003/http://www.kcchiefs.com/arrowhead |archivedate= August 30, 2009 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> which makes it the [[List of current National Football League stadiums|sixth-largest stadium]] in the NFL. The stadium underwent a $375 million renovation, completed in mid-2010, which included new luxury boxes, wider concourses and enhanced amenities.<ref name=\"Forbes\"/><ref name=\"Pioli to join\"/> The stadium renovation was paid for by $250 million in taxpayer money and $125 million from the Hunt Family.<ref name=\"Chiefs hire Cardinals\"/> The stadium cost $53 million to build in 1972, and an average ticket in 2009 costs $81.<ref name=\"Forbes\"/> [[Aramark]] serves as the stadium's concession provider and [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]], [[Anheuser-Busch]] and [[Coca-Cola]] are major corporate sponsors.<ref name=\"Forbes\"/>\n\nDating back to the Chiefs' home opener in 1991 to mid-2009, the Chiefs had 155 consecutive sellout games.<ref name=\"Forbes\"/> The streak ended with the final home game of the 2009 season against the Cleveland Browns, resulting in the first local TV blackout in over 19 years.<ref name=\"NFL's best fans\">{{cite web|title=NFL's best fans? We gotta hand it to the Steelers (barely)|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/preview08/columns/story?id=3530077|last=Mosley|first=Matt|publisher=ESPN.com|date=August 29, 2008|accessdate=January 14, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080831233745/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/preview08/columns/story?id=3530077|archivedate=August 31, 2008 }}</ref> Arrowhead has been called one of the world's finest stadiums<ref name=\"PFHOF\"/> and has long held a reputation for being one of the toughest and loudest outdoor stadiums for opposing players to play in.<ref name=\"Pioli to join\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Stadiums of the NFL \u2013 Arrowhead Stadium |url=http://www.stadiumsofnfl.com/afc/ArrowheadStadium.htm |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216013316/http://www.stadiumsofnfl.com/afc/ArrowheadStadium.htm |archivedate=December 16, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Arrowhead Stadium Quotes|url=http://zachishere.com/2006/11/23/arrowhead-stadium-quotes/|accessdate=December 31, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216071731/http://www.zachishere.com/2006/11/23/arrowhead-stadium-quotes/|archivedate=December 16, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Peter King Notes \u2013 The NFL\"/> All noise is directly attributed to its fans<ref name=\"NFL's Top 10 Fan Bases\"/> and was once measured at 116 [[decibel]]s by the Acoustical Design Group of [[Mission, Kansas]].<ref name=\"Chiefs ready\">{{cite news |url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4179/is_20040111/ai_n11810123 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005200006/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4179/is_20040111/ai_n11810123 |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 5, 2008 |title=Chiefs ready for playoff nemesis Indianapolis |work=Topeka Capital-Journal |date=January 11, 2004 |accessdate=December 31, 2008 }}</ref> By way of comparison, take-off of aircraft may lead to a sound level of 106 decibels at the ground.<ref name=\"Chiefs ready\"/> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' named Arrowhead Stadium the \"toughest place to play\" for opposing teams in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/0604/gallery.toughplaces/content.10.html|title=Sports Illustrated's 2005 poll: \"Toughest Places to Play\"|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=December 31, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216104740/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/0604/gallery.toughplaces/content.10.html|archivedate=December 16, 2008 }}</ref> The [[tailgate party]] environment outside the stadium on gameday has been compared to a \"college football\" atmosphere.<ref>{{cite news|title=49ers have to cope with the din of Arrowhead |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/10/01/49ERS.TMP&feed=rss.sports |last=Crumpacker |first=John |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=October 1, 2006 |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010020019/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2006%2F10%2F01%2F49ERS.TMP&feed=rss.sports |archivedate=October 10, 2008 }}</ref> Arrowhead Stadium features frequent [[Flypast#Entertainment and sports|fly-overs]] from a [[B-2 Spirit]] [[stealth bomber]] from nearby [[Whiteman Air Force Base]]. Since the [[1994 NFL season]], the stadium has had a natural [[grass]] playing surface.<ref name=\"This Week, February 2, 2008\">{{cite web|title=This Week in Chiefs History|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/02/22/this_week_in_chiefs_history1a/|date=February 2, 2008|accessdate=February 9, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307003743/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/02/22/this_week_in_chiefs_history1a/ |archivedate=March 7, 2008}}</ref> From 1972 to 1993, the stadium had an [[Artificial turf|artificial]] [[AstroTurf]] surface.<ref name=\"This Week, February 2, 2008\"/>\n\nDuring the game against the Oakland Raiders on October 13, 2013, Arrowhead Stadium once again became the loudest stadium in the world when the fans set the Guinness Book of World Records record for loudest crowd in an outdoor stadium (137.5&nbsp;dB), breaking the record set by the Seattle Seahawks just four weeks prior. A few weeks after, Seattle re-gained the record by reaching a noise level of 137.6 decibels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2013/10/13/4834950/chiefs-noise-record-guinness/in/4592497|title=Chiefs set new Guinness world record for stadium noise|author=Jon Benne|date=October 13, 2013|publisher=Vox Media|work=SBNation.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017114100/http://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2013/10/13/4834950/chiefs-noise-record-guinness/in/4592497|archivedate=October 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/Records-Broken/4ee1c72e-3ab4-4112-965a-eb8eaab5bf14|title=Records Broken|publisher=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015100547/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/Records-Broken/4ee1c72e-3ab4-4112-965a-eb8eaab5bf14|archivedate=October 15, 2013|access-date=October 13, 2013}}</ref> Chiefs fans have reclaimed the record once again on September 29, 2014, on [[Monday Night Football]] against the [[New England Patriots]], the fans recorded a sound reading of 142.2 decibels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chiefs Kingdom to be Featured on National TV|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/Chiefs-Kingdom-to-be-Featured-on-National-TV/992fea68-637f-41b9-b7e5-c1ffacc80e52|website=KCChiefs.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926035055/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/Chiefs-Kingdom-to-be-Featured-on-National-TV/992fea68-637f-41b9-b7e5-c1ffacc80e52|archivedate=September 26, 2014|access-date=September 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Training camp and practice facility==\n[[File:Mo-west-chiefs1.jpg|thumb|Summer camp at [[Spratt Stadium]] at Missouri Western]]\nWhen the franchise was based in Dallas, the team conducted their inaugural [[Training camp (National Football League)|training camp]] at the [[New Mexico Military Institute]] in [[Roswell, New Mexico]].<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> They moved camp to [[Southern Methodist University]], owner Lamar Hunt's [[alma mater]], for 1961 and continued to practice there until 1965.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> From 1966 to 1971, the Chiefs practiced in [[Swope Park]] in Kansas City,<ref name=\"Peterson 176\">Peterson, p. 176</ref> and from 1972 to 1991 held camp at [[William Jewell College]] in [[Clay County, Missouri]]\u2013where Lamar Hunt had extensive business dealings including [[Worlds of Fun]], [[Oceans of Fun]] and [[SubTropolis]].<ref name=\"History 90s\"/>\n\n[[File:011 KC Chiefs Practice Fields.jpg|right|thumb|Chiefs Practice Facility near Arrowhead Stadium]]\nFrom 1992 to 2009 the Chiefs conducted summer training camp at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013River Falls]] in [[River Falls, Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"Au Revoir, River Falls\">{{cite web|title=Au Revoir, River Falls |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/08/21/au_revoir_river_falls/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |last=Moris |first=Pete |date=August 21, 2009 |accessdate=September 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826114938/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/08/21/au_revoir_river_falls |archivedate=August 26, 2009 }}</ref> The Chiefs' 2007 training camp was documented in the [[HBO]]/[[NFL Films]] [[Documentary film|documentary]] [[reality television]] series, ''[[Hard Knocks (TV series)|Hard Knocks]]''.<ref name=\"Hard Knocks\">{{cite web |title=Chiefs to be featured in HBO's 'Hard Knocks' this summer|url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2007/06/02/chiefs_to_be_featured_in_hbos_hard_knocks_this_summer/|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=June 2, 2007|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609004240/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/06/02/chiefs_to_be_featured_in_hbos_hard_knocks_this_summer/ |archivedate=June 9, 2008}}</ref> Following the passage of a $25 million state tax credit proposal, the Chiefs moved their training camp to [[Missouri Western State University]] in [[St. Joseph, Missouri]], in 2010.<ref name=\"Chiefs announce plans\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs announce plans for 2009 training camp |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/12/chiefs_announce_training_camp_plans_for_2009/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=December 12, 2008 |accessdate=December 12, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217023859/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/12/chiefs_announce_training_camp_plans_for_2009/ |archivedate=December 17, 2008 }}</ref> The bulk of the tax credits went for improvements to Arrowhead Stadium with $10 million applied to the move to Missouri Western.<ref name=\"St. Joseph\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs to train in St. Joseph|url=http://www.joplinindependent.com/display_article.php/sen-com1229487152|work=Joplin Independent|date=December 16, 2008|accessdate=December 31, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401053742/http://www.joplinindependent.com/display_article.php/sen-com1229487152|archivedate=April 1, 2009 }}</ref> A climate-controlled, 120-yard NFL regulation grass indoor field, and office space for the Chiefs was constructed at Missouri Western adjacent to the school's [[Spratt Stadium]] before the 2010 season.<ref name=\"Chiefs training camp\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs training camp to return to Missouri beginning in 2010 |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/06/18/chiefs_training_camp_to_return_to_missouri_beginning_in_2010/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=June 18, 2009 |accessdate=June 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090622080222/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/06/18/chiefs_training_camp_to_return_to_missouri_beginning_in_2010 |archivedate=June 22, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOutside of training camp and during the regular season, the Chiefs conduct practices at their own training facility nearby Arrowhead Stadium. The facility is located near the Raytown Road entrance to the Truman Sports Complex just east of [[Interstate 435]] and features three outdoor fields (two grass and one artificial turf) as well as an indoor facility with its own full-size field.\n\n==Rivalries==\n{{see also|Chiefs\u2013Raiders rivalry|Broncos\u2013Chiefs rivalry|Chargers\u2013Chiefs rivalry|Governor's Cup (Missouri)}}\nThe Chiefs share intense rivalries with their three AFC West opponents, namely the [[Denver Broncos]], [[Las Vegas Raiders]], and [[Los Angeles Chargers]], with the Raiders rivalry considered one of the most bitter in the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/09/11/dishing-dirt-one-last-time-on-raiders-chiefs-rivalry/ |last=McDonald|first=Jerry|title=Dishing dirt one last time on Raiders-Chiefs rivalry |date=September 12, 2019 |website=The Mercury News |language=en-US |access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref> They also have had historical rivalries with the [[Seattle Seahawks]], who were a divisional rival until their reallocation to the [[NFC West]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kckingdom.com/2018/12/22/kansas-city-chiefs-used-big-time-rivals-seahawks/ |title=Kansas City Chiefs used to be big time rivals with Seahawks |first=Leigh|last=Oleszczak |date=December 22, 2018 |website=KC Kingdom |language=en-US |access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref> former AFL teams such as the [[Buffalo Bills]], and other AFC teams such as the [[Baltimore Ravens]] and [[Indianapolis Colts]]. In terms of NFC teams, the Chiefs faced off once in the Super Bowl against the [[Green Bay Packers]], and formerly shared a [[Governor's Cup (Missouri)|cross-state rivalry]] with teams located across the state of Missouri in [[St. Louis]], namely the [[St. Louis Cardinals (football)|Cardinals]] and [[St. Louis Rams|Rams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1255964-kansas-city-chiefs-top-non-divisional-rivals-currently |title=Kansas City Chiefs: The 5 Best Non-Divisional Rivalries |last=Vousoughian |first=Farzin |date=July 12, 2012 |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Mascots and cheerleaders ==\n[[File:KC Wolf.JPG|left|thumb|[[K. C. Wolf]], the Chiefs' mascot since 1989]]\nThe Chiefs' first mascot was [[Warpaint (mascot)|Warpaint]], a nickname given to several different breeds of [[pinto horse]]. Warpaint served as the team's mascot from 1963 to 1988.<ref name=\"Althaus 35\" /><ref name=\"mascots, cheerleaders\">{{cite web|url=http://www.georgeblowfish.com/Chiefspage7.html |title=Kansas City Chiefs mascots and cheerleaders |date=June 21, 2008 |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210211812/http://www.georgeblowfish.com/Chiefspage7.html |archivedate=February 10, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"McKenzie 141\">McKenzie, p. 141</ref> The first Warpaint (born in 1955, died in 1992) was ridden bareback by rider Bob Johnson who wore a full [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] [[headdress]].<ref name=\"Althaus 35\" /><ref name=\"mascots, cheerleaders\"/> Warpaint circled the field at the beginning of each Chiefs home game and performed victory laps following each Chiefs touchdown.<ref name=\"Althaus 35\" /><ref name=\"mascots, cheerleaders\"/> On September 20, 2009, a new Warpaint horse was unveiled at the Chiefs' home opener.<ref name=\"Warpaint returns\">{{cite web|title=KCUR: Warpaint returns to Arrowhead Stadium|url=http://www.publicbroadcasting.net/kcur/news.newsmain/article/1/0/1556766/KCUR.News/Warpaint.Returns.to.Arrowhead.Stadium|last=Echlin|first=Greg|publisher=KCUR|date=September 21, 2009|accessdate=September 21, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605232221/http://www.publicbroadcasting.net/kcur/news.newsmain/article/1/0/1556766/KCUR.News/Warpaint.Returns.to.Arrowhead.Stadium|archivedate=June 5, 2011 }}</ref> Warpaint is now ridden by a cheerleader, Susie.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/cheerleaders/warpaint.html |title=Warpaint |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |accessdate=November 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214185654/http://www.kcchiefs.com/cheerleaders/warpaint.html |archivedate=December 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1980s, the Chiefs featured a short-lived unnamed \"Indian man\" mascot which was later scrapped in 1988.<ref name=\"mascots, cheerleaders\"/> Since 1989 the cartoon-like [[K. C. Wolf]], portrayed by Dan Meers in a [[wolf]] costume, has served as the team's mascot.<ref name=\"Althaus 35\" /><ref name=\"K. C. Wolf\">{{cite web|title=K. C. Wolf|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/kcwolf/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610034554/http://www.kcchiefs.com/kcwolf/ |archivedate=June 10, 2008}}</ref> The mascot was named after the Chiefs' \"Wolfpack\", a group of rabid fans from the team's days at Municipal Stadium.<ref name=\"mascots, cheerleaders\"/> K. C. Wolf is one of the most popular NFL mascots and was the league's first mascot inducted into the [[Mascot Hall of Fame]] in 2006.<ref name=\"Mascot Hall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mascothalloffame.com/virtual/hall/index.html?staff_id=12|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130128231257/http://www.mascothalloffame.com/virtual/hall/index.html?staff_id=12|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 28, 2013|title=Mascot Hall of Fame \u2013 K. C. Wolf|publisher=Mascot Hall of Fame|accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe Chiefs have employed a [[Kansas City Chiefs Cheerleaders|cheerleading squad]] since the team's inception in 1960.<ref name=\"McKenzie 140\">McKenzie, p. 140</ref> In the team's early days, the all-female squad was referred to as the Chiefettes.<ref name=\"History cheer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/cheerleaders/history/|title=Kansas City Chiefs History \u2013 Cheerleaders |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822131959/http://www.kcchiefs.com/cheerleaders/history/ |archivedate=August 22, 2008}}</ref> In addition to the Cheerleaders, in the early 1970s, there was also a dance/drill team that performed for pre-game and halftime. From 1986 to 1992, the cheerleader squad featured a mix of men and women.<ref name=\"McKenzie 140\" /> Since 1993, the all-female squad has been known as the Chiefs Cheerleaders.<ref name=\"mascots, cheerleaders\"/><ref name=\"McKenzie 140\" /><ref name=\"History cheer\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notable players==\n{{Further|List of Kansas City Chiefs players|Kansas City Chiefs quarterbacks|List of Kansas City Chiefs first-round draft picks}}\n\n===Current roster===\n{{Kansas City Chiefs roster}}\n\n===Retired numbers===\n{{Kansas City Chiefs retired numbers}}\n\n===Pro Football Hall of Fame enshrinees===\nTwenty-three members of the Pro Football Hall of Fame spent at least some portion of their career with the Chiefs. Thirteen spent the majority of the career with the Chiefs. Ten of the Chiefs in the Hall of Fame were involved with the Chiefs during their [[Super Bowl IV|Super Bowl Championship]] season of [[1969 Kansas City Chiefs season|1969]]. The Chiefs have 3 contributors, 2 coaches, and 18 players in the Hall of Fame. In addition, Hall of Fame safety [[Ronnie Lott]] had a contract with the Chiefs during the 1995 season, but only played for the Chiefs in the preseason and spent the regular season on injured reserve and is not recognized by the Hall of Fame as having played for the Chiefs.\n\n{{Kansas City Chiefs Pro Football Hall of Fame}}\n\n===Chiefs Hall of Fame===\n[[File:Jan Stenerud.JPG|right|thumb|[[Jan Stenerud]]'s name was honored at Arrowhead Stadium's ring of honor{{Clear}}]]\nThe Chiefs are one of 16 organizations that honor their players, coaches and contributors with a team Hall of Fame or Ring of Honor.<ref name=\"Who's next\">{{cite web|title=Who's next for Chiefs Hall? |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/11/whos_next_for_chiefs_hall/ |last=Gretz |first=Bob |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=March 11, 2009 |accessdate=March 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316233849/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/11/whos_next_for_chiefs_hall |archivedate=March 16, 2009 }}</ref> Established in 1970, the Chiefs Hall of Fame has inducted a new member in an annual ceremony with the exception of the 1983 season.<ref name=\"Who's next\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs Hall\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City Chiefs Hall of Fame|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/hall_of_fame/|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609220445/http://www.kcchiefs.com/hall_of_fame/ |archivedate=June 9, 2008}}</ref> Several of the names were featured at Arrowhead Stadium in the stadium's architecture prior to renovations in 2009. The requirements for induction are that a player, coach, or contributor must have been with the Chiefs for four seasons and been out of the NFL for four seasons at the time of induction.<ref name=\"Who's next\"/> There are some exceptions, such as [[Joe Delaney]] and [[Derrick Thomas]], Delaney was with the team for only two seasons before his death, Thomas was inducted 1 year after his death in January 2000 (2 years after his final season). The Chiefs have the second-most enshrinees of any NFL team in their team Hall of Fame behind the [[Green Bay Packers]], who have enshrined over 100 players and team contributors over the years in the [[Green Bay Packers Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"Who's next\"/> Nineteen players and the coach of the [[Super Bowl IV]] championship team have been inducted into the ring of honor.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"5\" style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}}\"|'''Chiefs Hall of Fame'''\n|-\n! style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}}\"|Inducted\n! style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}}\"|No.\n! style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}}\"|Player\n! style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}}\"|Position\n! style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs}}\"|Tenure\n|-\n| 1970 || \u2014 || [[Lamar Hunt]] || Team founder/Owner || 1960\u20132006\n|-\n| 1971 || 36 || [[Mack Lee Hill]] || RB || 1964\u20131965\n|-\n| 1972 || 75 || [[Jerry Mays (defensive lineman)|Jerry Mays]] || DT || 1961\u20131970\n|-\n| 1973 || 84 || [[Fred Arbanas]] || TE || 1962\u20131970\n|-\n| 1974 || 42 || [[Johnny Robinson (safety)|Johnny Robinson]] || S || 1960\u20131971\n|-\n| 1975 || 88 || [[Chris Burford]] || WR || 1960\u20131967\n|-\n| 1976 || 55 || [[E.J. Holub]] || C/LB || 1961\u20131970\n|-\n| 1977 || 77 || [[Jim Tyrer]] || OT || 1961\u20131973\n|-\n| 1978 || 21 || [[Mike Garrett]] || RB || 1966\u20131970\n|-\n| 1979 || 16 || [[Len Dawson]] || QB || 1963\u20131975\n|-\n| 1980 || 78 || [[Bobby Bell]] || LB || 1963\u20131974\n|-\n| 1981 || 86 || [[Buck Buchanan]] || DT || 1963\u20131975\n|-\n| 1982 || 89 || [[Otis Taylor (American football)|Otis Taylor]] || WR || 1965\u20131975\n|-\n| 1983 || colspan=4|''No induction''\n|-\n| 1984 || 71 || [[Ed Budde]] || G || 1963\u20131976\n|-\n| 1985 || 63 || [[Willie Lanier]] || LB || 1967\u20131977\n|-\n| 1986 || 18 || [[Emmitt Thomas]] || CB || 1966\u20131978\n|- \n| 1987 || \u2014 || [[Hank Stram]] || Coach || 1960\u20131974\n|-\n| 1988 || 44 || [[Jerrel Wilson]] || P || 1963\u20131977\n|-\n| 1989 || 14 || [[Ed Podolak]] || RB || 1969\u20131977\n|-\n| 1990 || 51 || [[Jim Lynch (football player)|Jim Lynch]] || LB || 1967\u20131977\n|-\n| 1991 || 28 || [[Abner Haynes]] || RB || 1960\u20131964\n|-\n| 1992 || 3 || [[Jan Stenerud]] || K || 1967\u20131979\n|-\n| 1993 || 69 || [[Sherrill Headrick]] || LB || 1960\u20131967\n|-\n| 1994 || 58 || [[Jack Rudnay]] || C || 1969\u20131982\n|-\n| 1995 || 32 || [[Curtis McClinton]] || RB || 1962\u20131969\n|-\n| 1996 || 20 || [[Deron Cherry]] || S || 1981\u20131991\n|-\n| 1997 || 73 || [[Dave Hill (football player)|Dave Hill]] || OT || 1963\u20131974\n|-\n| 1998 || 67 || [[Art Still]] || DE || 1978\u20131987\n|-\n| 1999 || 34 || [[Lloyd Burruss]] || S || 1981\u20131991\n|-\n| 2000 || 35 || [[Christian Okoye]] || RB || 1987\u20131992\n|-\n| 2001 || 58 || [[Derrick Thomas]] || LB || 1989\u20131999\n|-\n| 2002 || 76 || [[John Alt]] || OT || 1984\u20131996\n|-\n| 2003 || 59 || [[Gary Spani]] || LB || 1978\u20131986\n|-\n| 2004 || 37 || [[Joe Delaney]] || RB || 1981\u20131982\n|-\n| 2005 || \u2014 || [[Jack Steadman]] || President/GM || 1960\u20131989\n|-\n| 2006 || 90 || [[Neil Smith (football player)|Neil Smith]] || DE || 1988\u20131996\n|-\n| 2007 || 29 || [[Albert Lewis (American football)|Albert Lewis]] || CB || 1983\u20131993\n|-\n| 2008 || 61 || [[Curley Culp]] || DT || 1968\u20131974\n|-\n| 2009 || 8 || [[Nick Lowery]] || K || 1980\u20131993\n|-\n| 2010 || \u2014 || [[Marty Schottenheimer]] || Coach || 1989\u20131998\n|-\n| 2011 || 31 || [[Kevin Ross (American football)|Kevin Ross]] || CB || 1984\u20131993, 1997\n|-\n| 2012 || 68 || [[Will Shields]] || OG || 1993\u20132006\n|-\n| 2013 || 26 || [[Gary Barbaro]] || S || 1976\u20131982\n|-\n| 2014 || 31 || [[Priest Holmes]] || RB || 2001\u20132007\n|-\n| 2015 || 24 || [[Gary Green (American football)|Gary Green]] || CB || 1977\u20131983\n|-\n| 2016 || 49 || [[Tony Richardson (American football)|Tony Richardson]] || FB || 1995\u20132005\n|- \n| 2017 || 88 || [[Carlos Carson]] || WR || 1980\u20131989\n|-\n| 2018 || 88 || [[Tony Gonzalez]] || TE || 1997\u20132008\n|-\n| 2019 || 54 || [[Brian Waters]] || G || 2000\u20132010\n|}\n\n==Head coaches==\n[[File:Andy Reid at Eagles training camp 2010-08-03.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[Andy Reid]] (pictured in 2010), began his first season as the Chiefs' head coach in 2013]]\n{{Main|List of Kansas City Chiefs head coaches}}\nThirteen head coaches have served the Texans/Chiefs franchise since their first season in 1960. [[Hank Stram]], the team's first head coach, led the Chiefs to three AFL championship victories and two appearances in the [[Super Bowl]]. Stram was the team's longest-tenured head coach, holding the position from 1960 to 1974.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/> [[Marty Schottenheimer]] was hired in 1989 and led Kansas City to seven playoff appearances in his 10 seasons as head coach.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/><ref name=\"History 90s\"/> Schottenheimer had the best [[winning percentage]] (.634) of all Chiefs coaches.<ref name=\"Schottenheimer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/SchoMa0.htm|title=Marty Schottenheimer's coaching record|publisher=Pro Football Reference|accessdate=July 9, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709084423/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/SchoMa0.htm|archivedate=July 9, 2008}}</ref> [[Gunther Cunningham]] was on the Chiefs' coaching staff in various positions from 1995 to 2008, serving as the team's head coach in between stints as the team's [[defensive coordinator]].<ref name=\"Chiefs name Gunther\"/><ref name=\"History 2000s\"/> [[Dick Vermeil]] coached the team to a franchise-best 9\u20130 start in the [[2003 Kansas City Chiefs season|2003 season]].<ref name=\"Curtain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/01/01/game_summary_bengals |title=Vermeil and the Chiefs in perfect harmony as the curtain falls with a 37\u20133 win |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |accessdate=July 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080317200318/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/01/01/game_summary_bengals/ |archivedate=March 17, 2008 }}</ref> Of the ten Chiefs coaches, [[Hank Stram]] and [[Marv Levy]] have been elected into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]], Levy, however, is more well known for his time with the Buffalo Bills.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hall of Famers by Franchise|publisher=Pro Football Hall of Fame |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/teams.html|accessdate=July 9, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080707032032/http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/teams.html |archivedate=July 7, 2008}}</ref> [[Herman Edwards]] served as the team's head coach from 2006 to 2008, compiling a 15\u201333 record and a franchise worst 6\u201326 record over a two-year span.<ref name=\"Chiefs fire Edwards\"/><ref name=\"Edwards relieved\"/><ref name=\"Edwards named\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/01/09/herm_edwards_named_the_10th_head_coach_in_kansas_city_chiefs_history2/ |title=Herm Edwards named the 10th head coach in Kansas City Chiefs history|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |accessdate=July 9, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070524000621/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/01/09/herm_edwards_named_the_10th_head_coach_in_kansas_city_chiefs_history2/ |archivedate=May 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"permission\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/01/06/chiefs_given_permission_to_talk_to_herm_edwards2/ |title=Chiefs given permission to talk to Herm Edwards|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |accessdate=July 9, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060510122419/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2006/01/06/chiefs_given_permission_to_talk_to_herm_edwards2/ |archivedate=May 10, 2006}}</ref> [[Todd Haley]] compiled a 19\u201326 record with the team from 2009\u20132011, including an AFC West division title in 2010.<ref name=\"Haley named\"/> Haley was fired with three games left in the 2011 season. [[Romeo Crennel]] was named interim coach, and was promoted to full-time coach in January 2012. Crennel was fired on Monday, December 31, 2012, after finishing the 2012 season with a 2\u201314 record. On January 5, 2013, the Chiefs hired [[Andy Reid]] to be their next head coach. In Reid's tenure, the Chiefs have been consistent contenders, making the playoffs in 6 of his 7 seasons as head coach, winning the division four times.\n\n==Ownership and administration==\n[[File:Clark Hunt.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Chairman of the Board and co-owner [[Clark Hunt]]]]\nThe franchise was founded in 1959 by Lamar Hunt after a failed attempt by Hunt to purchase an NFL franchise and relocate them to Texas.<ref name=\"Media 4\">Herb, Kuhbander, Looney, and Moris, p. 4</ref>  Hunt remained the team's owner until his death in 2006.<ref name=\"Media 4\"/> The Hunt family kept ownership of the team following Lamar's death and [[Clark Hunt]], Lamar's son, represents the family's interests.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite news|title=NFL team valuations: #20 Kansas City Chiefs|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2010/30/football-valuations-10_Kansas-City-Chiefs_309072.html|work=Forbes|date=August 25, 2010|accessdate=September 15, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928162827/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2010/30/football-valuations-10_Kansas-City-Chiefs_309072.html|archivedate=September 28, 2010 }}</ref> While Hunt's official title is CEO and [[Chairman|Chairman of the Board]], he represents the team at all owner meetings.<ref name=\"Clark Hunt\">{{cite web|title=Clark Hunt, Chairman of the Board|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/front_office/clark_hunt/|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610031039/http://www.kcchiefs.com/front_office/clark_hunt/ |archivedate=June 10, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Media 6\">Herb, Kuhbander, Looney, and Moris, p. 6</ref> In 2010, Hunt assumed role as [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] alongside his role as Chairman of the Board.<ref name=\"Thum steps down\"/> According to ''[[Forbes]]'', the team is valued at $2.4 billion and ranks 24th among NFL teams in 2017.<ref name=\"Forbes\"/>\n\nOwner Lamar Hunt served as the team's president from 1960 to 1976. Because of Lamar Hunt's contributions to the NFL, the AFC Championship trophy is named after him.<ref name=\"Media 411\">Herb, Kuhbander, Looney, and Moris, p. 411</ref> He promoted general manager [[Jack Steadman]] to become the team's president in 1977.<ref name=\"Media 411\"/> Steadman held the job until [[Carl Peterson]] was hired by Hunt in 1988 to replace him.<ref name=\"Media 411\"/> Peterson resigned the title as team president in 2008.<ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\"/> [[Denny Thum]] became the team's interim president following Peterson's departure and was officially given the full position in May 2009.<ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\"/><ref name=\"Thum named\">{{cite web |title=Denny Thum named Kansas City Chiefs president |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/05/08/denny_thum_named_kansas_city_chiefs_president/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=May 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515014705/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/05/08/denny_thum_named_kansas_city_chiefs_president |archivedate=May 15, 2009 }}</ref> Thum resigned from his position on September 14, 2010.<ref name=\"Thum steps down\">{{cite web|title=Denny Thum steps down from the Chiefs; Clark Hunt to be CEO|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/DENNY-THUM-STEPS-DOWN-FROM-THE-CHIEFS-CLARK-HUNT-TO-BE-CEO/9128f532-9b7d-4870-8adc-22f415572cde|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|date=September 14, 2010|accessdate=September 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917113401/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/article-2/DENNY-THUM-STEPS-DOWN-FROM-THE-CHIEFS-CLARK-HUNT-TO-BE-CEO/9128f532-9b7d-4870-8adc-22f415572cde|archivedate=September 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Don Rossi]] served as the team's general manager for half of the 1960 season, resigning in November 1960.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/> Jack Steadman assumed duties from Rossi and served in the position until 1976.<ref name=\"History 60s\"/><ref name=\"History 70s\"/><ref name=\"Media 411\"/> Steadman was promoted to team president in 1976 and despite being relieved of those duties in 1988,<ref name=\"Media 411\"/> he remained with the franchise until 2006 in various positions.<ref name=\"History 70s\"/><ref name=\"History 80s\"/> [[Jim Schaaf]] took over for Steadman as general manager until being fired in December 1988.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/> Carl Peterson was hired in 1988 to serve as the team's general manager, chief executive officer and team president.<ref name=\"History 80s\"/><ref name=\"Media 411\"/> Peterson remained in the position for 19 years until he announced his resignation from the team in 2008.<ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\">{{cite news|title=Chiefs' Carl Peterson resigns; Edwards' future uncertain|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/chiefs/2008-12-15-peterson-out_N.htm?csp=34|work=USA Today|agency=Associated Press|date=December 15, 2008|accessdate=December 15, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"press conference\">{{cite web|title=Chairman of the Board Clark Hunt Press Conference on the resignation of Carl Peterson |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/15/chairman_of_the_board_clark_hunt_pc/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=December 15, 2008 |accessdate=December 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218225808/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/15/chairman_of_the_board_clark_hunt_pc/ |archivedate=December 18, 2008 }}</ref> Denny Thum served as interim general manager<ref name=\"Chiefs' Carl Peterson\"/> until January 13, 2009, when the Chiefs named [[New England Patriots]] executive [[Scott Pioli]] the team's new general manager.<ref name=\"Pioli to join\"/><ref name=\"Pioli named\">{{cite web|title=Scott Pioli named Kansas City Chiefs general manager |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/01/13/scott_pioli_named_kansas_city_chiefs_general_manager/ |date=January 13, 2009 |accessdate=January 14, 2009 |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090118144247/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/01/13/scott_pioli_named_kansas_city_chiefs_general_manager/ |archivedate=January 18, 2009 }}</ref>\nPioli was released in early January after the hiring of Andy Reid, and was replaced by John Dorsey. Pioli's record as the Chief's general manager was 23\u201341.\n\nOn June 22, 2017, it was announced that the Chiefs had fired Dorsey.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chiefs, Dorsey Agree to Part Ways|url=http://www.chiefs.com/news/article-2/Chiefs-Dorsey-Agree-to-Part-Ways/90a06198-9204-404f-95a0-dec1e2b7d856|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710205426/http://www.chiefs.com/news/article-2/Chiefs-Dorsey-Agree-to-Part-Ways/90a06198-9204-404f-95a0-dec1e2b7d856|archivedate=July 10, 2017|access-date=July 11, 2017}}</ref> They hired [[Brett Veach]] as the new general manager on July 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/19956175/kansas-city-chiefs-promote-brett-veach-gm-spot |title=Kansas City Chiefs promote Brett Veach to GM spot |publisher=Espn.com |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710223007/http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/19956175/kansas-city-chiefs-promote-brett-veach-gm-spot |archivedate=July 10, 2017  }}</ref>\n\n===Staff===\n{{Kansas City Chiefs staff}}\n\n==Media==\n\n===Radio and television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|border=2}};\"|Kansas City Chiefs radio play-by-play announcers<ref name=\"Media 51\">Herb, Kuhbander, Looney, and Moris, p. 51</ref>\n|-\n|1960\u20131962\n|[[Charlie Jones (sportscaster)|Charlie Jones]]\n|-\n|1963\n|[[Merle Harmon]]\n|-\n|1964\u20131970\n|[[Tom Hedrick]]\n|-\n|1971\u20131973\n|[[Dick Carlson]]\n|-\n|1974\u20131975\n|[[Ray Scott (sportscaster)|Ray Scott]]\n|-\n|1976\n|[[Al Wisk]]\n|-\n|1977\n|Tom Hopkins\n|-\n|1978\u20131984\n|[[Wayne Larrivee]]\n|-\n|1985\u20131993\n|[[Kevin Harlan]]\n|-\n|1994\u2013\n|[[Mitch Holthus]]\n|}\n\nFrom 1989 until the team's Super Bowl LIV victory, [[Cumulus Media]]'s [[KCFX]], a.k.a. \"101 The Fox\", broadcast all Chiefs games on [[FM broadcasting|FM radio]] under the moniker of The Chiefs Fox Football Radio Network. Since 1994, [[Mitch Holthus]] has served as [[play-by-play]] announcer and former Chiefs quarterback Len Dawson serves as [[color commentator]].<ref name=\"Media 51\"/> Former Chiefs [[longsnapper]] [[Kendall Gammon]] serves as the field reporter.<ref name=\"Media 51\"/> Former Chiefs broadcaster [[Bob Gretz]] also contributes to the broadcasts. Starting in the [[2016 Kansas City Chiefs season|2016 season]], Dawson will only serve as color commentator during home games, and Gammon will be color commentator during road games, with Dani Welniak assuming Gammon's sideline reporting role for away games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hall Of Famer Len Dawson Reducing Role With Chiefs Radio Network|url=http://www.sunflowerstateradio.com/2016/07/14/hall-of-famer-len-dawson-reducing-role-with-chiefs-radio-network/|website=SunFlowerRadio.com|access-date=August 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821213515/http://www.sunflowerstateradio.com/2016/07/14/hall-of-famer-len-dawson-reducing-role-with-chiefs-radio-network|archive-date=August 21, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Chiefs and KCFX held the distinction of being the longest FM radio broadcast partnering tenure in the NFL.<ref name=\"Media 51\"/><ref name=\"101 The Fox\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/08/24/101_the_fox_extends_kansas_city_chiefs_radio_broadcast_rights_through_2009_season|title=101 The Fox extends Kansas City Chiefs radio broadcast rights through 2009 season|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|date=August 24, 2006|accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528224717/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/08/24/101_the_fox_extends_kansas_city_chiefs_radio_broadcast_rights_through_2009_season |archivedate=May 28, 2008}}</ref> The Chiefs Radio Network extends throughout the six-state region of Missouri, [[Kansas]], [[Iowa]], [[Nebraska]], [[Oklahoma]], and [[Arkansas]], with 61 affiliate stations.<ref name=\"Media 51\"/><ref name=\"101 The Fox\"/> \n\nWith the start of the 2020 season, [[Entercom]]'s [[WDAF-FM]] (106.5) will become the flagship of the Chiefs network, with sister station [[KCSP (AM)|KCSP]] (610) carrying surrounding analysis and team interview programming. The network's personnel, outside those exclusively contracted to Cumulus, are expected to be retained with the new Entercom contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kansascity.com/sports/nfl/kansas-city-chiefs/article238088264.html|title=Chiefs flagship radio station and broadcast partner moving on the dial in 2020|last=Kerkhoff|first=Blair|date=5 December 2019|work=[[Kansas City Star]]|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[KCTV|KCTV Channel 5]] ([[CBS]]) broadcasts most Chiefs regular season games, with exceptions as following. KCTV also broadcasts all Chiefs [[National Football League exhibition season|pre-season]] games. [[WDAF-TV|WDAF Channel 4]] ([[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]; that station is unrelated to WDAF-FM) broadcasts games in which the Chiefs host an NFC opponent, and carried the team's Super Bowl LIV victory. [[KSHB-TV|KSHB Channel 41]] ([[NBC]]) broadcasts all games in which the Chiefs play on ''[[NBC Sunday Night Football]]'' or NBC's NFL playoffs coverage. [[KMBC-TV|KMBC Channel 9]] ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]) has aired ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' games locally since 1970.\n\nPrior to the 1994 season, WDAF was the primary station for the Chiefs as an NBC affiliate (they aired on KMBC when ABC had the AFL package through 1964), since NBC had the AFC package. The inter-conference home games aired on KCTV starting in 1973 (when the NFL allowed local telecasts of home games). After week one of the 1994 season, WDAF switched to Fox (which got the NFC package), and has aired the Chiefs' inter-conference home games since. The bulk of the team's games moved to KSHB through the end of the 1997 season. Since that time, they have aired on KCTV, save for the 2015 Week 17 game vs. the [[Oakland Raiders]], which aired on WDAF when the NFL cross-flexed the game from CBS to FOX.\n\nAs of the 2015 preseason, the Chiefs preseason broadcasters were [[Paul Burmeister]] who serves as the play-by-play announcer, former Chiefs quarterback [[Trent Green]] serves as the color commentator, and KCChiefs.com insider B.J. Kissel is the sideline reporter.\n\n====Radio affiliates====\n[[File:Kansas City Chiefs radio affiliates.png|thumb|right|Map of radio affiliates.]]\nChiefs games are broadcast in Missouri and Kansas as well as parts of Iowa, Oklahoma, Nebraska, Arkansas, and South Dakota.<ref name=\"RadioAffiliates\">{{cite web|url=http://pro.kccrn-s.tritonflex.com/page.php?page_id=193 |title=Chiefs Radio Network Affiliate Team |publisher=Cumulus Media, Inc. |accessdate=June 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140501195734/http://pro.kccrn-s.tritonflex.com/page.php?page_id=193 |archivedate=May 1, 2014 }}</ref> Stations in major cities are listed below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|border=2}};\"|City !! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|border=2}};\"|Call sign !! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|border=2}};\"|Frequency\n|-\n| [[Kansas City, Missouri]] || [[WDAF-FM]] || 106.5 FM\n|-\n| [[Jefferson City, Missouri]] || [[KKLH]] || 100.1 FM\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Springfield, Missouri]] || KKLH || 104.7 FM\n|-\n| [[KGMY]] || 1400 AM\n|-\n| [[Joplin, Missouri]] / [[Pittsburg, Kansas]] || [[KKOW (AM)|KKOW]] || 860 AM\n|-\n| [[Manhattan, Kansas]] || [[KMAN]] || 1350 AM\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Salina, Kansas]] || [[KINA]] || 910 AM/107.5 FM\n|-\n| [[KSKG]] || 99.9 FM\n|-\n| [[Topeka, Kansas]] || [[KDVV]] || 100.3 FM\n|-\n| [[Wichita, Kansas]] || [[KNSS-FM|KNSS]] || 98.7 FM\n|-\n| [[Emporia, Kansas]] || [[KVOE-FM]] || 101.7 FM\n|-\n| [[Des Moines, Iowa]] || [[KBGG]] || 1700 AM\n|-\n| [[Omaha, Nebraska]] || [[KXSP]] || 590 AM\n|}\n\n===Preseason game affiliates===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|border=2}};\"|Metro area !! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|border=2}};\"|Call sign !! style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|border=2}};\"|Affiliation\n|-\n| [[Kansas City metropolitan area|Kansas City metro]] || [[KCTV5]] / [[KSMO-TV|KSMO]] || [[CBS]] / [[MyNetworkTV|MyTV]]\n|-\n| [[Columbia, Missouri]]<br />[[Jefferson City, Missouri]] || [[KMIZ]] / [[KQFX-LD|KQFX]] / [[KZOU]] || [[ABC Television|ABC]] / [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] / MyTV\n|-\n| [[Des Moines, Iowa]]<br />[[Ames, Iowa]] || [[KDSM-TV|KDSM]] || FOX\n|-\n| [[Ft. Smith, Arkansas]]<br />[[Fayetteville, Arkansas]]<br />[[Springdale, Arkansas]]<br />[[Rogers, Arkansas]]|| [[KNWA-TV|KNWA]] / [[KFTA-TV|KFTA]] || [[NBC]] / FOX\n|-\n| [[Joplin, Missouri]]<br />[[Pittsburg, Kansas]] || [[KODE]] / [[KSNF]] || ABC / NBC\n|-\n| [[Lincoln, Nebraska]]<br />[[Hastings, Nebraska]]<br />[[Kearney, Nebraska]] || [[KFXL-TV|KFXL]] / [[KHGI]] || FOX / ABC\n|-\n| [[Ottumwa, Iowa]]<br />[[Kirksville, Missouri]] || [[KTVO]] / [[KTVO]] 3.2 || CBS / ABC\n|-\n| [[Springfield, Missouri]] || [[KOLR]] / [[KOZL]] || CBS / Indy\n|-\n| [[St. Joseph, Missouri]] || [[KQTV]] || ABC \n|-\n| [[Topeka, Kansas]] || [[WIBW-TV|WIBW]] / EIBW || CBS / MyTV\n|-\n| [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]] || [[KOTV-DT|KOTV]] / [[KQCW]] || CBS / [[The CW|CW]]\n|-\n| [[Wichita, Kansas Metropolitan Statistical Area|Wichita metro]]<br />[[Ensign, Kansas]]<br />[[Hays, Kansas]]<br />[[Goodland, Kansas]] || [[KWCH]] / [[KSCW-DT]] / [[KDCU]] || CBS / CW / [[Univision]]\n|}\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Fan base===\n[[File:061123Broncos-Chiefs01.jpg|right|thumb|Arrowhead Stadium]]\nThe Chiefs boast one of the most loyal fan bases in the NFL.<ref name=\"NFL's best fans\"/><ref name=\"Insider grading\">{{cite web|title=Ranking the NFL: Insider grading on every franchise |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/9601836/Ranking-the-NFL:-Insider-grading-on-every-franchise |last=Schein |first=Adam |publisher=Fox Sports |date=June 2, 2009 |accessdate=June 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608081838/http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/9601836/Ranking-the-NFL%3A-Insider-grading-on-every-franchise |archivedate=June 8, 2009 }}</ref> Kansas City is the sixth-smallest [[media market]] with an NFL team, but they have had the second-highest attendance average over the last decade.<ref name=\"NFL's Top 10 Fan Bases\">{{cite web|title=NFL's Top 10 Fan Bases (Photo Gallery) |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/pgStory?contentId=8453940#sport=NFL&photo=8358342 |publisher=FoxSports.com |accessdate=January 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912220804/http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/pgStory?contentId=8453940 |archivedate=September 12, 2008}}</ref> Studies by [[American City Business Journals|Bizjournals]] in 2006 gave the Chiefs high marks for consistently drawing capacity crowds in both good seasons and bad.<ref name=\"Cleveland is No. 1\">{{cite news|title=Cleveland is No. 1 in ranking of NFL fan loyalty |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/edit_special/43.html |last=Thomas |first=G. Scott |publisher=Bizjournals |date=September 4, 2006 |accessdate=January 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011025525/http://www.bizjournals.com/edit_special/43.html |archivedate=October 11, 2008}}</ref> The Chiefs averaged 77,300 fans per game from 1996 to 2006, second in the NFL behind the [[Washington Redskins]].<ref name=\"Cleveland is No. 1\"/> The franchise has an official fan club called '''Chiefs Kingdom''' which gives members opportunities to ticket priority benefits and VIP treatment.<ref name=\"Chiefs Nation\">{{cite web|title=Welcome to Chiefs Nation! |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/chiefsnation/sign-in/|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|accessdate=January 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822085411/http://www.kcchiefs.com/chiefsnation/sign-in/ |archivedate=August 22, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"birth\">{{cite web|title=Lamar Hunt announces birth of Chiefs Nation|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/17/lamar_hunt_announces_the_birth_of_chiefs_nation/|publisher=Kansas City Chiefs|date=April 16, 2008|accessdate=January 5, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613140053/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/17/lamar_hunt_announces_the_birth_of_chiefs_nation/ |archivedate=June 13, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\" before home games, many Chiefs fans intentionally yell out \"CHIEFS!\" rather than singing \"brave\" as the final word.<ref name=\"McKenzie 132\">McKenzie, p. 132</ref> In 1996, general manager Carl Peterson said \"We all look forward, not only at Arrowhead, but on the road, too, to when we get to that stanza of the National Anthem... Our players love it.\"<ref name=\"McKenzie 132\" /> After the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]], Chiefs fans refrained from doing so in honor of those who lost their lives in the tragedy and continued to do so for the remainder of the 2001 season.<ref name=\"Giants beat Chiefs\">{{cite news|title=Giants beat Chiefs 13\u20133 in defensive struggle|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/news/2001/09/23/giants_chiefs_ap/|agency=Associated Press|work=Sports Illustrated|date=September 24, 2001|accessdate=December 31, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025143311/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/news/2001/09/23/giants_chiefs_ap/|archivedate=October 25, 2012 }}</ref> At the Chiefs' September 23, 2001, home game against the New York Giants, fans gave the opposing Giants a standing ovation.<ref name=\"Peter King Notes \u2013 The NFL\">{{cite news|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1023798/index.htm |title=Peter King Notes \u2013 The NFL |date=October 1, 2001 |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |work=CNN |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080329085703/http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1023798/index.htm |archivedate=March 29, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAfter every Chiefs touchdown at home games, fans chant while pointing in the direction of the visiting team and fans, \"We're gonna beat the hell outta you...you...you, you, you, you!\" over the song \"[[Rock and Roll (Gary Glitter song)|Rock and Roll Part 2]].\"<ref name=\"Celebration\">{{cite web|title=It's a Celebration: Best NFL Touchdown Rituals|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=3139628&type=story|last=Pahigian|first=Josh|publisher=ESPN.com|date=December 3, 2007|accessdate=January 16, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103122147/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=3139628&type=story|archivedate=November 3, 2012 }}</ref> The chant starts after the third \"hey!\" in the song.<ref name=\"Celebration\"/> The original version of the song by [[Gary Glitter]] was previously used until the NFL banned his music from its facilities in 2006 following the British rocker's conviction on sexual abuse charges in Vietnam.<ref name=\"Celebration\"/> A cover version of the song played by [[Tube Tops 2000]]<ref name=\"Celebration\"/> was used from 2006 until the 2015 season.<ref name=\"New Celebration\">{{cite web |last1=Grathoff |first1=Pete |title=The Chiefs are changing their TD celebration song and fans are furious |url=https://www.kansascity.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/for-petes-sake/article31752291.html |website=The Kansas City Star |publisher=The Kansas City Star |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Chiefs' fan base has expanded across the world like many other NFL teams. However, there is a [[Twitter]] account dedicated to Chiefs fans in the UK and has been recognized by the Kansas City Chiefs and is their official UK fan page. They have many dedicated fans writing articles and interviewing players of the team such as [[Tamba Hali]].<ref>[https://twitter.com/KCChiefsUK Arrowheads Abroad (KCChiefsUK) on Twitter]. Twitter.com. Retrieved on July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nArrowhead Stadium is also recognized by [[Guinness World Records]] as having the loudest outdoor stadium in the world. This was achieved on September 29, 2014 in a [[Monday Night Football]] game against the [[New England Patriots]] when the crowd achieved a roar of 142.2 [[decibels]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Chiefs break Guinness crowd noise record at Arrowhead against the Patriots|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/09/chiefs-break-guinness-crowd-noise-record-at-arrowhead-against-the-patriots|website=USAToday.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140930152604/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/09/chiefs-break-guinness-crowd-noise-record-at-arrowhead-against-the-patriots|archivedate=September 30, 2014}}</ref> which is comparable to standing {{convert|100|ft}} from a jet engine, which even with short term exposure, can cause permanent damage.<ref>{{cite web|title=Decibel (Loudness) Comparison Chart |url=http://www.gcaudio.com/resources/howtos/loudness.html|website=GCAudio.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Tomahawk chop ===\n{{main|Native American mascot controversy}}\n\nChiefs fans also carry on a tradition that began at Florida State University in the mid 1980s by using the Seminole WarChant as a rallying cry during key moments in their football games.<ref name=\"McKenzie 133\">McKenzie, p. 133</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1991-10-09/sports/9102100231_1_war-chant-tight-ends-decisions|title=The Tomahawk Chop-it's No Longer Just Fsu's|work=tribunedigital-sunsentinel}}</ref> Prior to each home game, a former Chiefs player<ref>{{cite web|title=Game Day Activities: Chiefs vs. Giants|url=http://www.chiefs.com/news/article-2/Game-Day-Activities-Chiefs-vs-Giants-/201c0f8d-a522-48f1-8339-62c92df6258d|website=Chiefs.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211075645/http://www.chiefs.com/news/article-2/Game-Day-Activities-Chiefs-vs-Giants-/201c0f8d-a522-48f1-8339-62c92df6258d|archivedate=February 11, 2017|access-date=February 9, 2017}}</ref> or famous Chiefs fan (such as NASCAR driver [[Clint Bowyer]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Clint Bowyer revs up Kansas City Chiefs' pregame tradition |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2018/12/09/clint-bowyer-kansas-city-chiefs-drum-pregame |website=NASCAR.com}}</ref> or rapper [[Tech N9ne]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Tech N9ne will be guest drummer and spirit leader at Arrowhead Sunday |url=https://fox4kc.com/2019/12/27/tech-n9ne-will-be-guest-drummer-and-spirit-leader-at-arrowhead-sunday/ |website=Fox4KC.com}}</ref>), called the honorary drum leader, bangs on a drum with a large drum stick to start the [[Tomahawk chop]].\n\nThe Chiefs' and their fans use of American Indian imagery and stereotypes has been the source of controversy, as some decry usage of symbols like the \"war drum,\" songs and spectacles like the \"Tomahawk Chop,\" and stereotypical dress of fans in faux war paint and headdresses.  In 2016, Native American groups asked the Kansas City Chiefs to stop doing the tomahawk chop.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ariel Rothfield |url=http://www.kshb.com/sports/football/chiefs/kansas-indigenous-group-asking-kansas-city-chiefs-fans-to-stop-the-tomahawk-chop |title=Kansas indigenous group asking Kansas City Chiefs fans to stop the Tomahawk chop |publisher=KSHB |date=January 15, 2016 |accessdate=February 23, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228081915/http://www.kshb.com/sports/football/chiefs/kansas-indigenous-group-asking-kansas-city-chiefs-fans-to-stop-the-tomahawk-chop |archivedate=December 28, 2016 }}</ref> In the same year a similar request was made of Exeter Chiefs.<ref>{{cite web |author=EdOldfield |url=http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/a-message-for-exeter-chiefs-from-the-cultural-ambassador-for-crow-creek-dakota-sioux-tribe/story-29597102-detail/story.html |title=A message for Exeter Chiefs rugby club from a member of the Crow Creek Dakota Sioux tribe |work=Exeter Express and Echo |date=August 8, 2016 |accessdate=February 23, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809123137/http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/a-message-for-exeter-chiefs-from-the-cultural-ambassador-for-crow-creek-dakota-sioux-tribe/story-29597102-detail/story.html |archivedate=August 9, 2016 }}</ref>  The Editorial Board of the Kansas City Star newspaper called for the cessation of the \"Tomahawk Chop\" in late 2019, noting opposition from Native Americans and Tribes, and stating that the practice stereotypes and dehumanizes Native Americans.<ref>{{cite web|author=Editorial Board |url=https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/editorials/article236882498.html|title=Stop the Offensive 'Arrowhead Chop.' It's Time for a New Chiefs Tradition |work=Kansas City Star |date=November 1, 2019 |accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Chiefs have escaped the more intense criticism of other teams using Native American names and logos, however attention increased in 2020 in advance of their appearance in [[Super Bowl LIV]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2020/01/27/tomahawk-chop-kansas-city-chiefs/| title=The Chiefs are bringing Native American imagery, and the 'tomahawk chop,' to a Super Bowl stage| author=Jacob Bogage| date=January 27, 2020| newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref> While there has been efforts to address other issues, such as fans wearing warpaint and headdresses, the \"chop\" and the accompanying chant is defended, including by some local Native Americans. However, in a national survey, half of Native Americans said the \"tomahawk chop\" bothered or offended them, rising to 65% among those more engaged in Native traditions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/29/sports/football/chiefs-tomahawk-chop.html?searchResultPosition=1| title=Celebrating the Kansas City Chiefs, the Chop Divides| author=John Eligon| date=January 29, 2020| newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Tony DiPardo===\nFrom various periods between 1963 and the 2008 season, [[trumpet]]er Tony DiPardo and The T.D. Pack Band played live music at every Chiefs home game.<ref name=\"Althaus 86\">Althaus, p. 86</ref><ref name=\"McKenzie 137\">McKenzie, p. 137</ref> The band was known as The Zing Band when the team was located at Municipal Stadium. DiPardo was honored by head coach Hank Stram in 1969 with a [[Super Bowl ring]] for the team's victory in Super Bowl IV.<ref name=\"Althaus 86\" /> When his health was declining, DiPardo took a leave of absence from the band from 1983 to 1988.<ref name=\"McKenzie 137\" /> DiPardo's daughter took over as bandleader in 1989, by which time DiPardo returned to the band by popular demand.<ref name=\"McKenzie 137\" /><ref name=\"Althaus 100\">Althaus, p. 100</ref> For the 2009 season, due to renovations at Arrowhead Stadium, the band did not return to perform at the stadium.\n\nDiPardo died on January 27, 2011, at age 98. He had been hospitalized since December 2010 after suffering a brain aneurysm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcactionnews.com/dpp/sports/football/chiefs/chiefs-band-leader-tony-dipardo-dies|title=Chiefs band leader Tony DiPardo dies|author=Justin Unell|date=January 27, 2011|publisher=KSHB 41 News, Kansas City|accessdate=January 27, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927212909/http://www.nbcactionnews.com/dpp/sports/football/chiefs/chiefs-band-leader-tony-dipardo-dies|archivedate=September 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Kansas City Chiefs seasons]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last=Althaus |first=Bill |year=2007 |title=The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly: Kansas City Chiefs: Heart-Pounding, Jaw-Dropping, and Gut-Wrenching Moments in Kansas City Chiefs History |publisher=Triumph Books |isbn=978-1-57243-928-3 }}\n*{{Cite book|last=Gruver |first=Ed |year=1997 |title=The American Football League: A Year-by-year History, 1960\u20131969 |publisher=McFarland Publishing |isbn=0-7864-0399-3 }}\n*{{Cite book|editor1-last=Herb |editor1-first=Patrick |editor2-last=Kuhbander |editor2-first=Brad |editor3-last=Looney |editor3-first=Josh |display-editors=3 |editor4-last=Moris |editor4-first=Pete |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2008 |title=2008 Kansas City Chiefs Media Guide |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs Football Club, Inc. }}\n*{{Cite book|last=Hoskins |first=Alan |year=1999 |title=Warpaths: The Illustrated History of the Kansas City Chiefs |publisher=Taylor Publishing Company |isbn=0-87833-156-5 }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Maske |first=Mark |year=2007 |title=War Without Death: A Year of Extreme Competition in Pro Football's NFC East |publisher=Penguin Group |isbn=978-1-59420-141-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/warwithoutdeathy00mask }}\n*{{Cite book|last=McKenzie |first=Michael |year=1997 |title=Arrowhead: Home of the Chiefs |publisher=Addax Publishing Group |isbn=1-886110-11-5 }}\n*{{Cite book|last=Peterson |first=John E. |year=2003 |title=The Kansas City Athletics: A Baseball History, 1954\u20131967 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=0-7864-1610-6 }}\n*{{Cite book|last=Stallard |first=Mark |year=2004 |title=Kansas City Chiefs Encyclopedia |edition=2nd |publisher=Sports Publishing, LLC |isbn=1-58261-834-8 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kansas City Chiefs}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.nfl.com/teams/kansascitychiefs/profile?team=KC Kansas City Chiefs] at the [[National Football League]] official website\n\n{{Kansas City Chiefs}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|border=2}}\n|list =\n{{NFL}}\n{{American Football League navbox}}\n{{Missouri Sports}}\n{{Native American mascot controversy}}\n{{Good article}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|American football|United States}}\n\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs| ]]\n[[Category:Dallas Texans]]\n[[Category:American Football League teams]]\n[[Category:National Football League teams]]\n[[Category:American football teams in Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Sports in the Kansas City metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1960]]\n", "name_user": "Rockchalk717", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChampionships", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kansas_City_Chiefs"}
